a((VKolkata: Meet the green traveller on a global mission.He has crossed 22,000 km in a wonder van without using a drop of diesel or any other fossil fuel. His van, fitted with a solar panel roof, runs on bio-fuel and aims to produce the least possible carbon footprint while going around the world. Andy Pag, a British mechanical engineer-cum-renewable energy exponent who reached Kolkata on Sunday, says largescale use of bio-diesel can make the carbon emission target of 2 tonnes per capita per year achievable.To reduce the risk of a 5?C rise in global temperatures from 50% to 3%, experts have agreed to reduce CO2 emissions to 2 tonnes per person per year by 2050. "Currently, the carbon footprint per capita per year in the UK is 10-12 tonnes per capita per year and 15-18 tonnes in the US. A massive development spree in India and China and explosion of automobiles have suddenly pushed it beyond 5-6 tonnes per capita per year from less than 2 tonnes in these two countries. As India and China have large populations, the impact is quite telling," said Andy Pag at Emami Tower, which houses Emami Biotech, the biggest producer of bio-diesel in eastern India.The bio-truck expedition, as Andy's trip is known, seeks to find out how other people are cutting their footprint while travelling on a "sustainable carbon budget" himself.Andy rebuilt his vehicle from "rubbish". He designed it to suit his needs with a 1,200-litre tank and filter to reduce viscosity of waste vegetable oil recycled from restaurants and individual kitchens. His solar panel ensures that his refrigerator runs uninterrupted and he gets enough light to study at night and charge his laptop."Europe has a very efficient network of recycling of waste oil from individual kitchens and restaurants. New ideas on sources of waste are being developed as commercial projects in the quest to meet the demand. Uptown Oils, one of my sponsors, is working with sewer grease, which has to be scraped out of drains," said Andy.However, the trip hasn't been as smooth as Andy had thought. Unaware of the laws of countries he passed through, his satellite phone landed him in jail once. "The experience in jail was quite enlightening," Andy wrote on his blog. "This court case has cost me Euro 6,000 while I spent about Euro 3,000 on three months of travel from the UK to India, which was meant to be one of the cheaper legs of the journey. My contingency cash has been wiped out." Also, his vehicle's windscreen was shattered by drunkards a couple of times.He left London on September 19 last year and crossed the English Channel. From France, it has been a long and eventful journey. "I travelled through Italy, Croatia, Turkey , war-ravaged Iran, Pakistan and entered India through Punjab on December 22. In Pakistan, I got an army escort to travel though Balochistan," he said.At Emami Tower, Andy filled up his tank, which he thinks would take care of his journey through Indonesia and Australia. "I strongly feel that India should clear all obstacles to commercial use of bio-diesel. This would be a great leap forward in reducing its carbon footprint." Andy is expected to leave Kolkata on August 10."Though the ministry of renewable energy is pushing for its use, the ministry of petroleum is creating stumbling blocks for its commercial use. So far, all bio-diesel plants in the nation are idle, thanks to the government's policies," said Aditya Agarwal , director of Emami Group of Industries.
