a((VNecessity was the mother of telecom sector invention in India. Rising capital expenditure and social & environmental resistance forced telecom operators to look at infrastructure sharing. Their need to cut operational costs and expand rapidly across geographies in the face of limited infrastructure availability and rising regulatory pressures aided the process.\u000a\u000aInfrastructure sharing practically started in 2005 with Quippo Telecom taking the lead and creating a demand for the concept in the market. Initially, when infrastructure sharing was not common, operators created and managed their own infrastructure, at huge costs. However, as the industry evolved, various cost benefits of infrastructure sharing came to the fore, prompting the players to adopt this concept.\u000a\u000aWith telecom tariffs going down at every turn, operators grappled with a sustained decline in their average revenue per user (Arpu). The global slowdown further impacted their investment plans, resulting in their quest for the innovative and cost-effective business model of infrastructure sharing.\u000a\u000aToday, almost 65-70% of an operators opex goes towards telecom infrastructure provisioning cost. According to various independent studies, a telecom operator offering wireless services can save up to 30% of capex and 15% of opex by sharing the telecom infrastructure.\u000a\u000aTelecom infrastructure sharing offers various cost and social benefits. Some of these include:\u000a\u000a* Benefits to end-consumers; from reduced costs for operators and the resultant lower cost of services. Infrastructure sharing also leads to increased availability of telecom services across wider geographies, further promoting competition and better services;\u000a\u000a* Benefits to new operators; to launch services rapidly across the length and breadth of the country through ready-infrastructure, and at much lower costs due to the reduction in their capital and operational expenditure. Reduced capex also releases cash that can be used for strategic corporate purposes;\u000a\u000a* Bridging the digital divide by helping the government achieve its objectives of increasing telecom penetration in rural India. Unless shared, the rollout of telecom services in rural India will be an unviable option for most operators;\u000a\u000a* Benefits to the environment by reducing the infrastructure requirements, like telecom towers, of operators. Infrastructure sharing also offers other benefits such as shared energy and maintenance bills, thus helping the operators, while benefitting the environment with reduced carbon emissions.\u000a\u000aWhile only passive infrastructure sharing is permitted in India, active infrastructure sharing is still under government consideration. Once allowed, these measures will further reduce costs for operators.\u000a\u000aIn the mature international markets, during various stages of growth, telecom operators adopted different forms of infrastructure sharing, namely site sharing, network sharing, intra-circle roaming, etc. These models facilitated speedy rollout and helped new entrants to significantly reduce time-to-market. As these markets matured, other forms of sharing also became relevant, such as spectrum sharing and MVNOs, which enhanced the sectors growth.\u000a\u000aToday, India is one of the largest and the fastest growing mobile markets in the world. An average addition of over 16-18 million new subscribers every month has put immense pressure on the existing telecom infrastructure. The launch of 3G and Wimax services will exert additional pressure on infrastructure, posing a challenge for operators to support this growth momentum. The astronomical bids seen during the 3G and BWA auctions have put a huge strain on the balance sheets of operators, and this strain can be eased by reducing their service and network rollout costs through infrastructure sharing.\u000a\u000aThese challenges offer a business opportunity to existing infrastructure companies. According to our estimates, the Indian market will see around 1.5-1.6 lakh additional tenancies with the launch of 3G and Wimax services. From less than 1.5 lakh towers in 2007, the industry today has grown to over 3.2 lakh towers. These facts highlight the growth potential the Indian market offers to telecom infrastructure companies.\u000a\u000aWhile the telecom infrastructure industry has seen tremendous growth in the last few years, it faces several challenges on its growth path. With the profitability of operators keep falling, managing telecom infrastructure-related capital and operating expenditure is becoming unmanageable. A high tenancy ratio is crucial for the viability of shared telecom infrastructure business, as higher the tenancy, the faster are the returns on investment. However, in a scenario where a large number of infrastructure players compete for enhanced market shares, getting higher tenancy becomes a key challenge.\u000a\u000aTelecom infrastructure sharing works on a business model that depends on multiple service providers rolling out their services simultaneously. Supporting the simultaneous rollout of new operators will need immediate investment in the network rollout programme. However, with the global financial meltdown, fund raising has become a difficult task for infrastructure players.\u000a\u000aWith rural India being the only bastion left for telecom operators, most of them are launching their services in these still-untapped markets. While a major chunk of new subscribers are coming from rural markets today, the falling Arpus have become a deterrent for the service providers to enter these geographies. Even if infrastructure players set up their sites in rural belts, recovering their costs by getting tenants remains a big challenge.\u000a\u000aThe telecom sector has played a vital role in the overall growth of the economy, amply supported by the innovative concept of infrastructure sharing. In todays extremely competitive market, the only way service providers can sustain their growth and profitability is through infrastructure sharing. This is the time they should focus all their energies on customer-centric initiatives, to create a differentiation in the marketplace to gain a competitive edge. In such a scenario, it is important for policy makers to come up with laws that are practical to be implemented at the grassroots level. Such policies should encourage infrastructure sharing among all operators.\u000a\u000aThe writer is CEO Quippo-WTTIL
