a((VNEW DELHI: The Times of India has always strived to keep issues on environment in focus, engaging its readers with burning topics and raging debates. In an initiative to bring science and issues surrounding climate change closer to the people, the group launched a compilation of essays on climate change on Thursday.`Climate Change, Society and Sustainable Development: Agenda for Action' was launched by agriculturalist M S Swaminathan at a ceremony hosted jointly by Times Foundation , supported by Times Group Books , and FICCI . The book encompasses 20 essays contributed by 20 authors and 10 co-authors. The essays have been listed under five main heads of `Impact and assessment issues', `Science, society and environmental education', `Financing market mechanism and food security issues', `Volunteering and CSR for a smart planet' and `Mitigation and adaptation strategies'."The book is highly comprehensive and deals with pertinent issues such as CSR and mitigation. Climate change largely affects poor nations and the poor in all nations. We also have to study and understand the societal impact of climate change and how it affects lives and livelihoods. Anticipatory mitigation measures are extremely important to take,'' said Swaminathan.Amit Mitra, secretary general, FICCI, also recommended the book for anyone who wanted to understand the politics, science and impact of climate change. "The book is remarkable, specially for the brilliant statistics with which it supports its claims. India is on the verge of market development and it is necessary to understand how to incorporate this with mitigation methods. We are importing technology from other countries but are they carbon-friendly. There has to be a collective fund for countries like India to help them in accessing mitigation measures,'' he said.UK High Commissioner to India, Sir Richard Stagg, who also attended the launch ceremony, said: "Developed countries have created the problem and should shoulder responsibility in reducing it. UK is doing a great deal but we are a small nation and might not be able to make much of an impact on a global scale. While the climate change discussions are being carried out at a political level, it is also necessary to address the underlying practical issues like encouraging forestation and technology transfer. India seems to underestimate its ability to contribute to technology though it has some of the best minds in the world.''
