a((VPANAJI: The energy emission released by the mining industry over its lifespan in Goa has been equal to "210 Hiroshima-sized bombs," said an energy expert on Saturday.Speaking at a press conference after a workshop on Carbon Footprint , Sagar Dhar, a consultant to the United Nations and a member on several government committees, said the damage to Goa has been done over several decades by the mining industry."The mining area for iron ore in Goa is 700 square km. The carbon footprint released by mining is computed at 15 tera joules per square km. That means the total energy released by mining has been 10,500 tera joules, which is equal to 210 Hiroshima-sized bombs," said Dhar. (The WWII atom bomb was codenamed Little Boy)."The energy released by one Hiroshima-sized bomb was calculated at 50 tera joules," he added. The day-long workshop in Panaji was attended by 65 participants including various social activist groups and students. Participants were taught how to compute carbon footprints and the results were later used for an analysis.The participants also computed the carbon footprint created by the tourism industry. The carbon dioxide emissions for foreign tourists was calculated at 1.3 metric tonnes (MT), while emissions for Indian tourists was calculated at 0.26 MT. The overall emission for tourism in Goa is 1.5 MT, Dhar said.To sequester these emissions, forest area is required and the current forest availability in Goa falls short of the requirement, he claimed.
