a((VWhat is biomass gasification?\u000a\u000aVillage electrification\u000a\u000aIndia has over 580,000 villages and many hamlets. In over 18,000 villages and hamlets grid electricity is to be provided. Even in villages where the state electricity grid is available, quality of power is poor, both in terms of voltage and duration of availability. The Government of India ( Ministry of New and Renewable Energy ) has introduced several schemes and financial incentives for electrifying these villages through renewable sources. Biomass gasification is one of the routes for tapping renewable sources of energy.Biomass is a naturally available substance from plants which store solar energy by the process of photosynthesis. It has been the major source of energy before discovery of fossil fuels and still is a source for cooking, and to some extent for industrial purposes in developing countries.Gasification is the process of converting biomass, which is largely available in the form of solid, to gaseous form through thermo chemical process. Biomass contains carbon and hydrogen, which on burning produces carbon dioxide and water vapour. These products, when passed over hot carbon bed (charcoal), are converted to hydrogen and carbon monoxide, which can be burnt as other gaseous fuels.The technology for biomass gasification is reasonably matured and can be utilised for electrification of villages. There are several advantages of this route for village electrification. Some of them are listed below:Biomass is available almost everywhere or can be grown. The fuel can be locally collected.Power will be available on demand at any time of the day or year. The device can be used for 24 hours continuously or for limited period per day. Different capacities from a few k ilowatts to Megawatt scale gasifiers are available. The power generated can be used for multiple applications like lighting, drinking and irrigation water supply, small scale industries, etc. Since the device can be used 