a((VPATNA: As part of International Year of Biodiversity celebrations and to create awareness about the importance of biodiversity in sustaining life on the earth, Shrikrishna Science Centre organised several events and activities for schoolchildren from August 17 to August 21.Delivering a lecture on `Climate change and water resources', Science College's geology professor Atul Aditya Pandey focused on the water resources like glaciers, surface run-offs and ground water and the impact of climate change on these resources.Even a little change in the temperature can affect the size and shape of glaciers, ultimately affecting all the perennial rivers, he said and added increased temperature, evaporation and precipitation also affect the pattern of rainfall. Rise in sea level due to melting of glaciers and ice caps can make a lot of fresh water saline, he said.Patna University's botany professor MP Trivedi spoke on the common medicinal plants available in Bihar. He said plant products are more acceptable to our body and herbal products have less side effects."During 25 years, we have developed 1000 drugs of which 50% are of plant origin,'' he said, adding 40% of the anti-cancer drugs are also of plant origin. Underlining the need to conserve plants and trees like Neem, Tulsi, Brahmi, Kalmegha, Ashwagandha and Ashoka, he asked the students to do their bit in popularizing the use of medicinal plants.Patna Women's College principal Sister Doris D'souza, called in to deliver a lecture on the fourth day of the series, dwelt at length on how human interventions are destroying the rich biodiversity. To prevent this, she said, students need to be motivated and sensitized through field trips, film shows on environment etc.Speaking on the last day, RK Sinha, popularly known as `Dolphin Man', said there is a need to look for a different source of energy generation instead of making large dams. The highlight of his lecture was the information about Ganga dolphins.Several informative movies were screened for the students on the occasion, and they included `The Last Dance', `The Hunted', `Turtles In A Soup', `Once There Was A Purple Butterfly', `Leopards In The Lurch', `The Silenced Witness', `Diminishing Resources', `Climate's First Orphans' and `The Weeping Apple Tree'.At the end of the programme, prizes were distributed to the winners of a poster-making contest on the topic, `Biodiversity of our land', in which 160 students from 16 schools participated. Rashmi Ranjan, a class XI student of Government Senior Secondary School-Gardanibagh, and Juhi Bareria, a class IX student of St Annes High School-Patna City, were adjudged winners in the senior and junior categories respectively.
