a((VThe findings of a national study determining changing patterns of forest and grasslands over a period of 10 years will be sent to UNFCCC (United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change),with an aim to find the reasons of change in these natural habitats.\u000a\u000aDr TP Singh,associate professor at the city based Symbiosis Institute of Geoinformatics (SIG),is leading the team studying the changes in Maharashtra,Gujarat and Rajasthan.\u000a\u000aThe UNFCCC is a multilateral treaty that was born at the United Nation’s Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED),the objective of which is to stabilise the concentration of green house gases in the atmosphere at a level that would prevent dangerous anthropogenic interference with the climate system. Being a party,India is required to furnish information on the implementation of convention in the form of national communication report. The country has been divided into various zones. Once all the zones are done with their researches,the results will be sent to the Ministry of Environment and Forest which would send the collective report to the UNFCCC.\u000a\u000aApart from SIG,other institutes which are part of the survey are National Remote Sensing Centre,Indian Institute of Remote Sensing,International Institute of Information Technology (IIIT),Hyderabad,and Ministry of Environment and Forest. Speaking about the work being done in the project,Dr Singh,who is the principal investigator for the three states,said,“This project holds a lot of importance in determining and predicting future patterns of changes of the environment. The first phase of the project in which we had to find out what kind of changes have taken place in the forests,wetlands and grasslands of these areas,is almost coming to an end.”\u000a\u000aIn the second phase of the project,the various institutes will work on finding out what can be done to minimise the changes. “In the first phase,we came across some alarming results. The vegetation in the border areas of all the three states and the forest patterns have changed within a time span of 10 years. There has been massive deforestation in many areas. Almost 8.7% forests have undergone a major change where many endangered plant species are getting lost. Hence in the second phase,we will try to narrow down the research and concentrate on the reasons as to why the number of particular plant in a forest has declined,” said Singh.\u000a\u000aAnother task of the project is to estimate carbon stocks and emissions and removal of greenhouse gases associated with land use,land use change and forestry (LULUCF) activities.\u000a\u000a“The primary importance of the project is that the changing patterns of the nation over the period of ten years will be clear,based on which we can predict changes that might take place in the coming years. The river basins and courses are changing,glaciers are melting leading to the rise in the sea-level. This study can be an effective tool to control climate change,” said Singh.\u000a\u000aThe meeting to discuss the plans for the second phase will take place in the month of September. “After the meeting,the work on the second phase will be started early next year. We have great hopes from the outcomes of the project based on our findings,the government can formulate future policies related to forests.”\u000a\u000aFor all the latest Pune News, download Indian Express App
