 a crucial document that has to be detailed out to prepare a state-level policy and action plan," said a scientist involved in the project.In the framework, effects of global warming and climate change and their resultant impacts in health, water resource, agriculture, livelihood, economic growth and sustainability in Bengal are outlined.The rise in temperature is projected to widen the transmission window of many vector species like malaria and dengue mosquitoes due to extension of warmer and more humid periods. The people living in the Hills, so far not exposed to vector-borne diseases, may become more susceptible due to lack of inherent immunity.Scarcity of food grains due to climate change may also increase cases of malnutrition and make a large population more susceptible to diseases.Melting of Himalayan glaciers will initially cause flooding of the Gangetic plains; then, the river's flow will become lean, triggering a water crisis in the region. "Scarcity of water and increase of extreme events in Haldia, the state's industrial hub, can jolt the entire development process," the framework report warns."The forest and biodiversity may also change drastically over a short time span as the climate becomes inhabitable for certain species. This will disrupt the food chain. Loss of forest barrier in the Sunderbans will multiply the susceptibility to storm surges and cyclones," the report stated.Rise in sea level will pose major socio-economic challenges as well. People living along the coastline will be forced to migrate as the land gets inundated. Displacement of a huge population in Bangladesh will also have a ripple effect on Bengal."Bengal has to make modifications in its policy to make it climate-proof and robust enough to endure the severe impacts of climate changes," reasoned a scientist.
