a((VNEW DELHI: Environment minister Jairam Ramesh might have been taken to task by the Opposition back home, but he has got a pat on his back from the US for the role he played over successive climate meets -- in Copenhagen last year and Cancun recently -- during negotiations, and helping broker the climate deal.The US appreciation of India's \u2018fundamental shift' in the stance at the controversial Copenhagen talks in 2009 and Ramesh's effort 'drawing India farther from the G77' has been revealed in a WikiLeak cable, dated February 2010, released on late Thursday night.Ramesh's role in brokering a deal in Cancun, on the other hand, won him plaudits from the US in public domain with the US special envoy Todd Stern recently pointing out in an interaction with media, "India really played a particularly constructive role in trying to find solutions that would bring everybody to the table. And one good example of that is on the issue of transparency, which was very important."While praising the dramatic shift in India's stance, the US seemed to have shifted the goal posts yet again. Todd Stern in the same media interaction said, "...we're not prepared to enter into legally binding commitments to reduce our emissions unless China, India, and so forth, are also prepared to do that."Under the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, India is not obliged to undertake any legally binding commitments but the developed world has been pushing to change that since 2007. So far, India had refused to take on any international commitments though it had, as per the convention, taken on responsibilities such as voluntary actions. But in Cancun, India made a dramatic U-turn with environment and forests minister making an unscripted intervention to state, "all countries should take on binding commitments under appropriate legal form".The US and other countries had, at least in public domain, only been talking of asking India and other emerging economies to take concrete voluntary actions to reduce their future emissions. UPA-II, too, had claimed that it was looking for binding commitments from the US as part of the new global deal and from other rich countries under the Kyoto Protocol. But the Cancun Agreements, that India played critical role in brokering, read along with the minister's unilateral proposals has altered that position radically.Going into Cancun, US had made international scrutiny of emerging economies its priority on the climate front. Ramesh had made a proposal despite lack of consensus within BASIC (Brazil, South Africa, India and China) on how to scrutinise India and other emerging economies' climate actions, part of which found their way into the Cancun Agreements.Stern appreciated Ramesh's role, saying, "India made a proposal that I think people fundamentally came around. The ultimate language wasn't exactly what India suggested, but it was really quite important that India did that."WikiLeak cable also showed that after the controversial Copenhagen Accord, US had noted, "The 16th Conference of Parties (COP-16) at Copenhagen marked a fundamental shift in India's climate change position," and "Ramesh has drawn India farther from the G77 by telling parliament India was not in the same category as other developing countries..."Post-Copenhagen, Ramesh had admitted to flexibility in the UPA's position on the climate negotiations, but in Cancun he called his dramatic U-turn as 'nauncing' India's position.
