a((VVARANASI: Now synthetic aperture radar (SAR) images are coming up for improved disaster-monitoring, besides providing time for preventive measures to mitigate the damages from natural disasters, if they occur again in the particular area.Talking to TOI on Wednesday, Dharmendra Singh, associate professor, department of electronics and computer engineering, IIT-Roorkee , said that the SAR technology that uses satellite datasets for analysing images generated through RADAR SAT-1 on C-band has shown better map depiction. It clearly shows changes occurring between two image acquisitions of the same area with desired temporal space.Saying that the technology has already been used for identifying shrinkage and subsidence of New Orleans city in US after Katrina hurricane in 2005, he also emphasised that it promises better disaster monitoring in the country that has already suffered natural disasters in the form of Tsunami and earthquakes.It may be mentioned here that Singh was in the city on Wednesday to attend the three-day international conference on geophysical sciences, energy, climate change and evolution of human society (ICON GSECCES-2010), organised by the department of geophysics, BHU. Singh has worked on a project funded by Canadian Space Agency between 2005 and 2008.Saying that the SAR images had provided detailed account of horizontal and vertical displacement after devastating hurricane in US, Singh also emphasised that data analysis and findings showed that the city was witnessing shrinkage at astonishing rate of six millimetres per year.A number of factors including groundwater withdrawals and drainage of organic soil were taken into consideration and the studies showed interesting results in the form of subsidence of the city. The images could be used for detecting subsidence in coal fields of the country, he added.Meanwhile, the second day of the seminar witnessed presentations and discussions on a number of issues related to energy, meteorology and disaster management using climate modelling and mapping.
