a((VVARANASI: While solar constant-- an important factor for determining weather change-- has long been interpreted as a constant factor, the new studies and researches have shown that the factor is not only a variable but is also governed by uneven distribution of Sun energy emanating from the Sun rays, which is leading to wrong predictions of monsoon and climate change."The solar constant is, in fact, a variable and no laws of science (physics) could predict accurate weather conditions and climate changes by considering it a constant factor," said senior scientist and head, Climatology and Hydrometeorology Division, Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology (IITM), Pune, NN Singh while talking to TOI on Thursday. Saying "accurate predictions of weather conditions and climate change are as difficult as anything," he also emphasised "even recent innovation like reanalysis of data from recorded instruments that are kept strategically over a place and satellite surveys have failed to yield error-free results."Singh, an alumnus of department of geophysics, Banaras Hindu University, was in the city on Thursday to attend the concluding session of the three-day international conference on geophysical sciences, energy, climate change and evolution of human society (ICON GSECCES-2010), also marking the diamond jubilee celebrations of the department (1949-2009)."A number of factors associated with weather forecasting keep changing over a particular area and so is the energy distribution of Sun rays," said Singh. He is also the founder head of the division run under the Ministry of Earth Sciences, New Delhi. Factors including air pressure, density and temperature not only decrease while going upwards, there is a difference even while going horizontally. The major difficulty arises while considering mean of the variations over a period of time to predict climate change and, more often than not, it is not error-free and there are lot of variations in these factors in different regions.However, Singh also said based on long calculations and mathematical models, the scientists had come close to predicting draught conditions in different parts of the country. The global warming may be a menace for the world but, for scientists, it gives interesting cues about draught conditions.The predictions based on the scientific model indicate that if the global mean temperature is around 15.6 degree Celsius, areas like Rajasthan, West Bengal, Bihar and parts of Jharkhand are likely to witness heavy rainfall while parts of central India and Indo-Gangetic plain could witness draught. However, situation could reverse if the global mean temperature is brought down to nearly 15.2 degree Celsius.Meanwhile, the three-day international conference also concluded on Thursday with presentations of natural disaster, climate change and energy.
