a((VSpecial Correspondent\u000a\u000aStrict enforcement of environmental regulation guidelines called for\u000a\u000aCHANDIGARH: Punjab, Haryana and Chandigarh will face serious challenges due to climate changes including scarcity of water and power, said Prodipto Ghosh, a member of the Prime Minister\u2019s Council on Climate Change, at a seminar on \u201cClimate, Carbon and Copenhagen\u201d here on Wednesday. The seminar was organised by the Society for Promotion of Science and Technology in India at Panjab University here.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe region shall face problems of fresh water from November to June as well as increased pressure on electricity demand due to high temperatures in summer, which could also mean a possible increase in incidence of malaria, dengue and so on.\u201d\u000a\u000aDr. Ghosh suggested strict enforcement of the Building Energy Code and environmental regulation guidelines for new structures, retrofitting existing buildings for energy efficiency and water conservation, mandatory water harvesting in all apartment blocks (new and existing) and government/corporate/large buildings, and promotion of energy service companies (ESCOs) to enable energy efficiency/water conservation measures to earn carbon credits.\u000a\u000aReferring to the failure of the Copenhagen summit, he said none of the participating countries was serious about climate change and they were, in fact, \u201cindulging in economic negotiations and future trade patterns\u201d.\u000a\u000aInaugurating the seminar, Punjab Chief Secretary Subodh Aggarwal reiterated the need to take proactive steps to combat global warming.\u000a\u000aHaryana Principal Secretary (Environment) Dr. G. Prasanna Kumar said: \u201cOur generation has already done great damage to the environment and we must take measures to reduce energy consumption and look for alternative sources of sustainable livelihood now.\u201d\u000a\u000aSenior scientist Dr. Ashok Sahni, however, was more optimistic about the changing global climate as a consistent phenomenon but affirmed that water being in limited supply on the planet needed to be conserved.\u000a\u000aAshwagosha Ganju, Director of Snow and Avalanche Studies Establishment, said the water shortage in the Himalayan region was turning grave and efforts were on to initiate measures like snow harvesting.\u000a\u000aSociety for Promotion of Science and Technology in India president and former Haryana Chief Secretary Dharam Vir said society was promoting science education at school level from Class I onward with a sharp focus on learning through experiments and exploration, establishment of mobile labs and awareness programmes of considerable importance.
