a((VNEW DELHI: With a concerted effort to question the intensity of climate impact, Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) chairman R K Pachauri talks with ET about the high cost of undermining the findings of science.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHow do you, as IPCC chief, view the Copenhagen Accord?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aStatus of accord is not clear. There is some sense of intent, particularly the intent of some countries. There are elements for building on what was agreed to by some countries. Of course, to extend this understanding to all the countries presents a daunting challenge.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Copenhagen Accord refers to the 2 degrees celsius temperature threshold, however there is complete silence on specific emission reduction targets. As IPCC chief are you satisfied with the acknowledgement given to science?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFor the first time the UNFCCC community accepted the principle of 2 degrees celsius. This flows out of the IPCC fourth assessment report, and is an acknowledgement of the impact of climate change and the attractiveness of mitigation action. However, there is total disregard for the emission reduction required to ensure that the temperature threshold is met. As I pointed out at the recent Delhi Sustainable Development Summit, if we don\u2019t bring about this reduction then we will reach overshoot scenario. If we continue to increase emission, it will lead to a temperature increase of beyond the 2 degrees threshold. At that time, we will have to take more stringent action, which will be more expensive and the impact of climate change will be even more drastic. This would be undesirable. I have consistently said it is better to take a long-term view and take measures now to stabilise temperature.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBetween now and Mexico, how do you see the IPCC reinforcing this idea that emission must be cut drastically and that the developed world will have to take the lead?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aI have been speaking to the developed world about the plight of the developing world. This is what forms the ethical basis for developed countries to give assistance to developing countries. Between now and Mexico, I plan to draw attention to the fact that it is important to realise the disadvantages of inaction and the attractiveness of action.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThis is not mere rhetoric. There are several economic models which bear this out. Take Japan, following the oil price shock of the seventies, Japan seriously undertook the task of radically restructuring their economy. This formed the basis of their growth. More recently, Germany has undertaken an aggressive renewable energy programme. Korea has a green growth programme. There are enough details for developing a different energy path, and its benefits in areas like agriculture.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOn the road to Mexico I plan to address groups of government, civil society, the public and stakeholders and draw attention to the benefits of action.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aScience has been the basis of the negotiating strength of the developing countries. However, a series of reports are now questioning the intensity of the climate change outlined by the IPCC report. Weakening the science only serves to undermine negotiating strength. How does IPCC plan to ensure that the intensity of climate change is mapped out better?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe IPCC will work to strengthen the hands of sane elements. The recent spate of reports is part of a concerted effort to undermine science through trivial issues. The attacks have increased especially as there is a renewed political commitment to deal with climate change. There is now a US president who is committed to taking action on climate change, that is big move from the eight years of the Bush administration. The IPCC is ready to listen to any ideas to strengthen it.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBy questioning the intensity of climate change, there is an effort to lower the quantity of finance that is required to be made available to developing countries to deal with climate change. How does the IPCC plan to step in to ensure that this doesn\u2019t happen?\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe emphasis of the IPCC is to carry out scientific analysis that is policy-relevant. There are countries that don\u2019t have the capacity to deal with impacts of climate change. In that sense the implications of climate change are far greater for the prosperous countries. In the Netherlands, 26% of land is under sea level and 29% is prone to flooding, given the lack of capacity. There is a need to realise that some countries face the real prospect of becoming failed states. We need to create an understanding that we are all together on this spaceship earth. And beyond a point we can\u2019t go on as we are now. There is a need to convince the public, especially in the developed countries of these realities.
