a((VNEW DELHI: With Shyam Saran 's exit, the government could now be looking at a change in the core climate negotiating team, which guides India's stance in international talks. The move, which has been pending at the level of the PMO for months now, could become the first clear signal after the Copenhagen talks of where PM Manmohan Singh stands on the climate tussle between the `flexibility' brigade and those wary of the elasticity of policy Union environment minister Jairam Ramesh has come to represent.While the shakeup in the core team, formed in March 2008 by the orders of the cabinet secretary when the institutional structure to respond domestically and internationally to the emerging issue was set up by the PMO, was initially proposed to expand and include officials from key ministries like finance, policy circles are keen to see if the critics of the minister, such as Prodipto Ghosh and Chandrashekhar Dasgupta, will be shunted out in the process.The PMO has not shown willingness to move on the issue despite different groups pushing for a radical change in the core team, which includes serving and retired government officials. But the minister's continued strained relations with the negotiators and the `retirement' of the PM's special envoy has, after they were first voiced before the Copenhagen meet in 2008, again raised head -- is the PM, the minister and the Congress party on the same page when it comes to altering stance at the climate talks.While the issue may not influence immediate domestic politics, the party is seen to understand the link of the negotiations to the future prices of electricity -- an aam admi concern.Reacting to the latest controversy over Ramesh's bid to discount the per-capita principle, Congress spokesperson Manish Tiwari said, "Providing commercial energy to 550 million Indians identified in the Integrated Energy Policy as well as fuelling an economy that is expected to grow at 8-10% over the next decades must be juxtaposed against the need to preserve planet Earth. That minimalist imperative may be doctrinal."While the PM has underlined the same concerns in several public speeches, his action or inaction on several ocassions has sent out conflicting signals. Ramesh on his own part has always claimed that he had won the flexibility mandate from not only the PM, but the Cabinet and Parliament too. The Cabinet in December last cleared the note for negotiations that had held on to most of the critical red lines though the minister had come back from the Copenhagen talks suggesting that he had stepped away from the Cabinet clearance on just one issue but only with the blessing of the PM who was present towards the end of the contentious meet at the Danish capital.Shyam Saran, sources told TOI, too had found it difficult to gauge the mood in the PMO on the prickly issue and found himself wedged between the minister in charge taking a clear radically new line and the top not providing a decisive brief for him to pursue.
