a((VFrom what N Anil Kumar, 46, an ocean scientist with the Goa-based National Centre for Antarctic & Ocean Research (NCAOR) packs into his bag, his sons know whether or not to ask him to take them along. When their dad is stuffing polar clothing into the backpack it means he will be away for a few months, usually in Antarctica , where the temperature dips to minus 89 degrees Celsius. As Kumar and his team of 19 scientists leave for the Southern Ocean - the first such expedition after the Copenhagen meet - the world will be eagerly awaiting new scientific evidence on global warming and its impact. The Southern Ocean, that extends between 35° and 60° south latitudes circling the Antarctic region, is an area that scientists the world over believe is vastly unexplored and pregnant with indications of not just the present and future of climate change, but also its past.Ferrying the team of scientists from different research laboratories across the country will be Sagar Nidhi. "It is India's only 'ice' classified vessel fit for a polar expedition. Its five labs can house 30 scientists," says D Rajasekhar, head of the vessel management cell at the National Institute of Ocean Technology, Chennai.This will also be the first time that Indian scientists will be crossing the 55° south latitude to go almost up to the polar region on an Indian vessel. Sagar Nidhi will leave Goa on January 11 for Mauritius and head farther southwards up to 66° south in the Antarctic region."The scientists will take up about 20 studies in the ocean between 35° and 66° south latitudes," says NCAOR director Rasik Ravindra. Prominent among them would be paleoclimatic studies that involve collecting samples from the ocean bed at a depth of up to six kilometres."Sagar Nidhi has equipment that can reach the ocean bed at a depth of up to 6,000 metres and drill seven metres to collect sediments. Changes in sediment formation, water mass and other parameters would be compared with previous data to ascertain the impact of climate change," says Anil Kumar, who leads the team of scientists.NCAOR has been collating data from the region since its first Southern Ocean expedition in 2004. Roughly, the region between 35° and 60° south is considered the Southern Ocean. Beyond it lies the Antarctic. Scientists have to compare data of at least 10 years to see the effect of climate change, and this mid-point expedition is of great importance. Despite expeditions by the US and Japan in the Southern Ocean, and those by India, Australia and South Africa south of the Indian Ocean, the ocean encircling the Antarctic region remains under-explored."The Southern Ocean, defined as the oceanic area south of 35°S, is known to be a very important region in shaping global climate, resulting from active atmosphere-ocean-ice interactions. The ocean is the source for several intermediate and deep water masses of the world. Many aspects of its circulation, water masses and the response of the Southern Ocean to climate change remain unknown primarily due to the lack of high resolution ship observations. This has led to a growing interest in exploration of the region to understand geological, physical, chemical and biological processes and their driving mechanisms operating in this region. The ocean is characterised by large seasonal variability in its environmental conditions, which influence the global climate," says Ravindra.India, now building 'Bharti,' the nation's third permanent research centre in Antarctica, already has a strong presence in the polar region. In spite of the scientific and logistics expertise gained over the years, a wide gap exists in our knowledge of the Southern Ocean, admits the NCAOR director. Another major study the fourth expedition will take up is how organisms adapt to sudden and extreme changes in temperatures. "Between 40° and 41° south latitudes, the ocean temperature drops suddenly from 20° to 9° Celsius. Learning how these organisms adapt to this change will have applications in several fields," adds Kumar.Trying to understand the complex integrated behaviour of the Indian Ocean Sector of the Southern Ocean has been a thrilling experience for scientists. "The scientific results are giving new insights every time we explore," says Ravindra.PLUMBING THE DEPTHSThe men will be carrying cutting-edge equipment to probe deep watersOn Board Sagar NidhiICE class vessel capable of taking up polar explorations Dynamic positioning system helps it stay steady even in strong currents Drop keel allows equipment to be dropped several feet directly below the hull of the vessel Silent ship with no noise interference while doing acoustic testsHIGHT OF THE SHIP 18 mLENGTH OF THE SHIP 103.6 mDRAFT 4.2 mDEAD WEIGHT 1,500 MTFUEL CAPACITY 900 CuMFRESHWATER CAPACITY 350 CuMCOST Rs 232 CrTYPE ICE Class - 1CMANUFACTURER FincantieriSCIENTISTS ONBOARD 20Deep Sea Multi Beam Echo SounderUses multiple beams to measure the vertical depth of the sea up to 10,000 metres by using ultrasound echoElectro Mechanical Cable 25 mm, 8000 mPower-cumdata cable used for coring of seabed and collection of sediments, sand and rocks from the floor for experiments on board the shipShallow Water Single Beam Echo SounderUses the same principle as the deep sea multi beam echo sounder, but uses a single beam to measure the depth of the sea up to 2,000 metresDeep Sea CTD with RosetteThe equipment collects water samples from a depth of up to 6,000 metres, doing away with the need for divers. It also gauges temperature and water currents at different depthsAcoustic Doppler Current ProfilerSubmersible equipment which does vertical profiling of water currents and measures the salinity and turbidity of sea waterSub Bottom ProfilerUltrasonic equipment that profiles the sea floor. The binary data collected is converted into a two-dimensional picture of the sea bed with basic details.
