a((VPUNE: Solar lanterns provided to villages where access to electricity is absent or minimal, as part of The Energy and Resources Institute 's ( TERI ) ' Lighting a Billion Lives ' (LaBL) programme, are now customised for rural lighting and come at a low cost.Akansha Chaurey, director, Decentralized Energy Solutions, and head of the LaBL programme said that the programme had been aiming at bringing down the cost, while enhancing their performance.LaBL is being implemented in nine villages in the districts of Ahmednagar, Amravati and Raigad. "Maharashtra comes in the priority list and the programme will be implemented in 12 more villages in Amravati and Ahmednagar districts by August this year. The idea is to replace kerosene and paraffin lanterns with solar lighting devices," she said.According to Chaurey, solar lanterns have proved to be a clean, reliable and versatile source of lighting. "At present, we have customised the lanterns for rural lighting," she said. Earlier, a lantern used to cost Rs 2,200 to Rs 3,000. With the new technology, it will cost around Rs 995 to 1,600.On Friday, TERI launched five categories of lanterns based on LEDS (light emitting diodes) that are tested in-house and are ready to be used in rural lighting initiatives. Three hamlets in Barshet, Belachiwadi and Hondawadi from the Alibaug block in Raigad district, which do not have access to electricity, are using these lanterns.Jayant Sarnaik, deputy director of NGO Applied Environmental Research Foundation (AERF), who is also the implementing partner of the LaBL programme in Maharashtra, said: "This technology is easy to install and economically viable. One has to pay just Rs 2 per day for using this lantern, which is used as maintenance cost. Solar lanterns are recharged at a village solar charging station and rented out to them.""TERI pays 60 per cent of the cost and the rest is co-financed by AERF and the German consulate in Mumbai," he added.Ranjit Deshmukh, senior research associate of city-based energy group 'Prayas' said, "Use of solar lanterns is a step forward in replacing kerosene-based lighting. It is an intermediate step towards rural electrification. Kerosene usage results in pollution and carbon emissions. But most importantly, expense on kerosene forms a big portion of the income of poor households."Maharashtra has nearly 100 per cent electrification, with only about 257 unelectrified villages. However, the number of households without access to electricity is estimated at several lakhs, even after the implementation of the Rajiv Gandhi Grameen Vidyutikaran Yojana, Deshmukh added.
