a((VJAIPUR: Heavy rain in the desert districts of Barmer and some parts of Jaisalmer in the last few days has raised flood scare.In August 2006, the usually drought prone Barmer district was hit by flash flood, causing death of 104 people, mainly in the villages of kawas and Malwa. Kharif crop worth Rs 1,300 crore was damaged and about 75,194 cattle perished in the flood.Similarly, the neighbouring district of Jaisalmer was also hit by flood in June this year. Rain, due to cyclone Phet, caused havoc in the district. In fact, two villages in Jaisalmer were completely cut off and the Army was called in to assist in rescue operation. About 15,000 livestock also perished in the rain. The rain also disrupted rail and road connectivity in the region.Pokhran in Jaisalmer reported one of the highest rainfall of this season in the last few days. Dhorimana in Barmer witnessed 98 mm of rain till Sunday morning taking the total rain to 339.5 mm. Baitu reported a cumulative rainfall of 240 mm till now.Barmer district collector Gaurav Goyal said though heavy rain has been reported in the district in the last few days, the situation is under control. "We are keeping a close watch on the situation," he said.Vivek Laul, department of earth sciences, Pondicherry University, who studied the Barmer flood in 2006, in his research report said, "Waterlogging is a major problem in western Rajasthan because of the presence of Bentonite and gypsite deposit in the area."The study also noted that in the absence of any effective drainage and negligible downward percolation of water, the conditions worsened and took the shape of a disaster. Keeping in view the frequency of the problem of waterlogging and floods in the above areas, proper water-management approach is required to reduce the loss of life, property, agricultural products and materials in future.Proper water management may include development of a network of canals/minor canals for draining out water for its utilisation in irrigation and storage purposes, construction of suitably spaced wells and bore wells for recharging well-identified aquifers, channelising water to already identified palaeochannels and unused barren depressions, construction of more water tanks and enlarging existing tanks and ponds to increase their waterstorage capacity.United Nation's World Meteorological Organization in July 2003, had warned of an increase in frequency of extreme weather events because of climate change. The deluge in Rajasthan was caused by a low pressure zone over the area, itself a result of extreme heat conditions, experts note.Low pressure in deserts that results from extreme heat is referred to as thermal low' in meteorological parlance. Such conditions could be caused by global warming, experts say.
