a((VANGUL: Orissa is trying to make hay while the corporate sun is shining on it, but industrialization seems to have taken the toll on the state's Angul-Talcher belt , a highly polluted area, thanks to the large number of coal mines, and power and steel industries. It even figures in the list 10 critically polluted areas of the country.A report prepared by IIT-Delhi and the Central Pollution Control Board (CPCB) has placed the belt in the seventh position. So much so, the air, water and soil of the area, known for the state's hottest temperature as well, have been seriously affected."Coal dust, fly ash, flouride content and unplanned transportation activities are some of the main causes for pollution in the Angul-Talcher area. The dust afloat in the local air, generated due to mining activities in Talcher area, settles down on water bodies in its vicinity, polluting the water as well as the air. Fine particles dispersed over a larger area by the faxtories also make it difficult for people to breathe," it is alleged.Secretary of the Nature Environment and Wildlife Society (News), Angul, Prasana Kumar Behera alleged that the heavy deposition of dust particles on the surface of drinking water, vegetation and other materials have become a regular feature in the area. "Due to non-compliance to emission and discharge norms by the power plants and coal mines, fluoride contents, toxic wastes, heavy metal and other industrial pollutants have contaminated the water, air and soil. Fire from the coal mines have become a regular feature, resulting in the rising temperature in the region. These are the main causes for the climate change and have created several health hazards for both people and environment," he alleged.Prasanta Kumar Pradhan, a resident of Dera village, located close to the coal mines, alleged that more than 16 people have died and many more been affected by diseases like tuberculosis, asthma, skin cancer and other stomach and heart problems in this village in the past one year.Despite repeated reminders to the local administration and the state level departments, no one did much to check pollution levels here, he alleged. He demanded a special team should be formed to investigate into the matter and take appropriate steps to normalize the condition of the soil, water and air of the region.According to a study report, humans are not at risk as long as the dust particles are below 200 microns. But in Talcher, the air has been found to be laden with particles as big as 500 microns and sometimes even above that.Additional district medical officer (ADMO), Angul, Ajaya Kumar Das has confirmed that diseases like tuberchulosis, asthma, skin cancer, flurosis, bronchitis, thyroidism, stomach and other ailments are commonplace in this region.
