a((VPUNE: Air pollution in Pune, one of the three problems which the city has to deal with urgently, is rising due to an increase in vehicles on the road.The Environment Status Report (ESR), a report card on the health of the city, which was tabled by The Energy and Research Institute (TERI) on Wednesday said immediate steps to improve the air quality are a must.Air pollution in Pune has become a serious' problem. The respiratory suspended particulate matter (PM 10) in the air is more than the standard national level. This has resulted in respiratory ailments. The ESR also said that dust rising from the roads was pushing up the PM10 level .The survey done by the air quality monitoring cell of the Pune Municipal Corporation (PMC) has said that roads contribute hugely to the air pollution."Vehicles plying on pucca roads blow 6,456 tonne dust every year while the dust raised by vehicles plying on kuccha road is 1,229 tonne every year. Though India has norms to control vehicular pollution, there is no norm related to road dust management," the ESR said.The rise in industrial activities around Pune has also contributed in the air pollution. "Small and medium industries are responsible for 303 tonne PM10 emission every year. Fossil fuels used in slums contribute to the air pollution. About 93,000 commercial properties which include hotels, malls and hospitals emit 204 tonne PM10 every year," the ESR said.Several measures were suggested by the report. One was an increase in the frequency of the public transport buses and a strengthening of the system to ensure that personal vehicles are not on the roads.The report also suggested the use of green fuel to bring down pollution. Public transport must be the mode of transport and projects like monorail and metro should be executed, the ESR said.A curb on adulteration of fuel, strict checking of vehicular pollution, and a control over use of generators was mooted.Pune's population has grown from 17 lakh in 1991 to an estimated 3