a((VChina\u2019s planned domestic action of 20% reduction in energy intensity of GDP by end-2010 over 1990 levels as a part of its current national plan will reduce 1.5 billion tonnes per year, which is more than the 1 Gt reduction planned in the US till 2020, and China is on course to meet this target. China will account for slightly less than half of global reduction in emissions pledged subsequent to the Copenhagen Accord.THE low level of pledges of developed countries will leave poor countries, including India, with no carbon space for economic growth, as collectively they would need as much carbon budget as the developed countries are about to take up from now till 2050, that is about 4.5Gt, or a third of the remaining carbon budget, if they were to just reach patterns of resource use that are common for all countries.Existing and affordable technologies will not enable this kind of economic growth without a significant per-capita carbon emissions increase, whereas carbon space is not even assured for countries with energy services below the global average.At Copenhagen, the 80% cut in emissions by 2050 proposed by developed countries would have fixed their share of the atmospheric space at two tonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent per-capita per year, leaving developing ones to fight among themselves for less than half that amount over the coming decades. Clearly , how the issue is framed is important.There are also problems with the way emission reduction is accounted under the current framework. The total amount of surplus emission credits is large enough to allow developed countries to follow a business-as-usual path till after 2020, while still complying with the currently-announced emissions targets.The accounting rules have loopholes. Generous emission targets under the Kyoto Protocol have added as much as 1.4 Gt of \u2018hot air\u2019 per year that can be sold even though they do not represent a real reductions in emissions.Including emissions from land use and the choice of a base year can amount to a reduction of as much as 1Gt for developed countries. For instance, Canada\u2019s recent pledge of a target of 17% reduction from the 2005 level will amount to 3% increase above the 1990 level, excluding emissions form the land use and forest sector.Recent estimates show that these loopholes would allow industrialised countries to increase actual domestic greenhouse gas emissions by 2-3 Gt, and overall reductions in emissions of developed countries would be only 3% below 1990 levels in 2020. Absolute emission reduction is the only measurement relevant to the goal of stabilising the global climate, as well as for comparability.The time has come for a new paradigm that will develop burden-sharing criteria to close the gigatonne gap, modify consumption patterns and match joint research and transfer of technology in the industry, electricity generation and agriculture sectors with mitigation/adaptation results so that patterns of resource use are common for all countries.
