a((VNEW DELHI: Parliament security has said it is ready to let in members on bicycles, in what can add a novel feature to the transport system among politicians.Security authorities have veered round to the view that not much needs to be done to make the system, geared for four-wheelers, bicycle-compatible. Sources said security staff can just establish the identity of MPs at the entrance while letting the bicycle in.Authorities are looking for a designated parking slot for cycles . Sources said the `RF tag', which ensures genuineness of the car registered against an MP, may not come into play in case of cycles. After bicycles are let in, they can be put to anti-sabotage tests.It may bring to fruition a fledgling attempt by some MPs to let their "transport" raise awareness about climate change. They made the request to Speaker Meira Kumar recently and the latter liked the idea enough to order quick action. "It is only a few MPs right now, but I am sure it will catch on," she told TOI. Even if it was symbolic, she said symbols played a big role in raising awareness.A beginning is surely on the cards. Bhartruhari Mahtab, BJD MP from Cuttack, welcomed it. "I expect the MPs to come to Parliament on cycles at least once a week," he told TOI. He said the request is aimed at helping raise awareness about climate while reducing congestion on Delhi roads. "Finally, it is also about physical fitness," he said.Delhi roads may not be the safest for cyclists, now known as a poor man's transport, but Mahtab feels the Parliament move can improve it. "It is time we created awareness on traffic sense and safeguarded the right of way of cyclists," he said.Rajiv Pratap Rudy of BJP, member-convenor of parliamentary forum on climate change, said cycle was an eco-friendly mode of transport and hoped the security found a way out. Delhi roads, he said, may make the move symbolic. But he added that another suggestion for `green cars' as ferry vehicles in Parliament was a practical step and 