a((VCHENNAI: Tamil Nadu , which has been reeling under power shortage, is yet to embrace eco-friendly technology in a big way to save electricity consumption.While nearly 11.5 lakh Compact Fluorescent Lamps (CFL, better known as energy saving light) have been distributed to households in Haryana, Chattisgarh and Andhra Pradesh under the "Bachat Lamp Yojna"(BLY), Tamil Nadu has still not implemented the scheme due to the lack of suppliers for the lamp. The state has over one crore domestic electricity consumers.Some companies had applied for the tender to the Tamil Nadu Electricity Board (TNEB) which is handling the BLY scheme for the state, for supplying the lamps. But nothing concrete has emerged yet."One of the major factors is quality of the lamps supplied. Most of them are not meeting the standards. Then there is the cost factor involved. The suppliers have to first distribute the lamps and claim their money back on a cost recovery basis (claiming carbon credits after supplying to the consumer). We heard that the suppliers conducted a survey in Coimbatore and other districts and found that not many people are interested in changing the lamps. We have not got any proper reply from them directly," said a senior TNEB official.A senior official of the Union power ministry pointed out that a few days ago the Union minister of state for power; Bharatsinh Solanki had informed the Rajya Sabha that four lakh bulbs in Yamunanagar, Haryana and in Rajnandgaon District, Chhattisgarh respectively and 3.5 lakhs bulbs in Vizag, Andhra Pradesh have been distributed under the BLY.A few days ago, union minister of state for power Bharatsinh Solanki had informed the Rajya Sabha that Andhra Pradesh, Assam, Punjab, Haryana, Maharashtra, Chhattisgarh, Kerala, Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Orissa, Himachal Pradesh, Goa, Tripura and Karnataka have shown interest in participating in the BLY. But Tamil Nadu is no where in the picture.In India, the lighting needs of the domestic sector are met by incandescent bulbs which are extremely energy inefficient. Nearly 95% of the electricity is converted in heat and just 5% is used for lighting. Lighting accounts for about 20% of electricity consumption and by use of CFL lighting the load can be reduced without compromising on the lumen output.Under the BLY scheme 60 Watt and 100 Watt incandescent lamps have to be replaced with 11 to15 Watt and 20 -25 Watt CFLs respectively. The CFLs will be distributed to the households by the suppliers themselves at Rs 15 per bulb which will be compensated to the CFL supplier by harnessing Clean Development Mechanism of the Kyoto protocol (claiming carbon credits).If the scheme takes off in Tamil Nadu at this juncture when it is facing a power crisis, it would be of great help for the State. "There are nearly 1 crore domestic consumers in the State and if each of them save power, hundreds of MWs can be saved. But we do not have the funds to do it ourselves," said the TNEB official.
