a((VStaff Reporter\u000a\u000a\u201cScience first\u201d model can fail to evaluate \u201creal\u201d adaptation options\u000a\u000a\u2018Rather than starting with science, climate change analysis can be approached with problem'\u000a\u000a\u2018Adaptation should be embedded in financial, economic development and social planning'\u000a\u000aBANGALORE: The social sciences, with their insights into social, economic and political realities, can shed light on the issues surrounding climate change in ways that science cannot do, said Judith Rees, director of the Grantham Research Institute on Climate Change and Environment at the London School of Economics, UK.\u000a\u000a\u201cScience has to be put in its proper place,\u201d said Prof. Rees, delivering a lecture on \u2018Adaptation to Climate Change: Policy, Economics and Governance' at the Indian Institute of Science (IISc) here on Friday.\u000a\u000aThe \u201cscience first\u201d or \u201cpredict-then-act\u201d model can fail to evaluate \u201creal\u201d adaptation options and is often top-down, she said, citing the example of the IPCC's (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change) risk assessment.\u000a\u000aRather than starting with the science, Prof. Rees suggested that the analysis of climate change be approached with the problem \u2014 such as how many dwellings need to be built or what policies need to be drafted.\u000a\u000aHowever, both scientists and social scientists will be evaluating the impact of climate change under \u201cgreat uncertainty\u201d \u2014 be they the ability of ecosystems to adapt, or behavioural responses, she said.\u000a\u000aGlobal negotiations and debates on climate change focus essentially on measures to mitigate the problem or reduce emissions, largely neglecting adaptation strategies, Prof. Rees added.\u000a\u000a\u201cAdaptation is the Cinderella of the climate change business,\u201d she said, likening it to an \u201cinsurance policy.\u201d Adaptation helps meet the challenge of sustaining economic and social growth while dealing with climate change.\u000a\u000aAdaptation policies needed to address several social sciences questions, Prof. Rees said. \u201cWhere and when should adaptation measured be taken up? Who pays adaptation costs?\u201d\u000a\u000aAdaptation \u201cmust not be just crisis management, it should be embedded in financial, economic development and social planning,\u201d she added.\u000a\u000aProf. Rees' lecture was part of the IISc-UK Lecture series.
