a((VAdvertising Standards Authority (ASA) of UK has ruled that a Oxfam poster stating that people are dying because of climate change 'was not misleading', dismissing complaints that the assertion could not be proven. ASA had received four complaints saying that the statement linking people dying due climate change was misleading and could not be substantiated.\u000a\u000aThe charitys poster ad campaign which said: "People dying thanks to climate change is a long way off. About 5,000 miles, give or take ... Our politicians have the power to help get a climate deal back on track."\u000a\u000aOxfam claimed that a number of reputable organisations, including the World Health Organisation, had published research proving this was true.\u000a\u000aThe ASA investigated the claim, and agreed that there was "robust consensus" that there was "extremely strong evidence for human-induced climate change".\u000a\u000a"We noted that Oxfam's claim was reasonably restrained in that it stated deaths were occurring at the present time as a result of climate change but that it did not claim specific numbers of deaths were attributable and it did not speculate about future numbers of deaths," added the UK watchdog.\u000a\u000aOxfam said it hoped the ASAs ruling would make people understand that climate change was having a real impact across the world.\u000a\u000aMartin Sorrell: We're back to LUV-shaped recovery\u000a\u000aWPP chief executive officers Sir Martin Sorrell has said that an "LUV"-shaped recovery is expected for 2011 as different countries continued to recover at different speeds. He also said that the advertising group's growth was at its strongest for 10 years.\u000a\u000a"LUV" shaped recovery describes a complex global picture: L-shaped in western Europe, U-shaped in the US and V-shaped in the so-called Bric nations of Brazil, Russia, India and China.\u000a\u000aWe might see a rebalancing next year I think next year is more likely to be LUV-shaped," he said speaking at a conference in Berlin. "The world is operating at different speeds there is no doubt about that. There are three levels of growth: the Brics at the top, the US and Germany in the middle and slow growth western Europe, which includes the UK, at the bottom."\u000a\u000aNew creative effectiveness category at Cannes Lions\u000a\u000aThe Cannes International Advertising Festival will add an effectiveness category next year. The festival organizers said in a statement that the new award, to be called Cannes Creative Effectiveness Lions, will honour creativity "which has shown a measurable and proven impact on a client's business -- creativity that effects consumer behavior, brand equity, sales and, where identifiable, profit." Only work that was shortlisted or a Lion winner at this year's festival is eligible to compete for an effectiveness award in 2011. This year the festival shortlisted about 2,325 entries, or about 10% of the total work entered. The festival said that the criteria for the new award will be results, accounting for 50% of an entry's score, along with strategy (25%) and idea (25%). The festival cautioned that the data in all entries will be checked by the external auditors at PricewaterhouseCoopers.\u000a\u000aUK leads the world in online shopping\u000a\u000aIf you thought the US was the biggest online shopping market, think again. It is UK with its 100 billion internet economy that leads the world in online shopping.\u000a\u000aUK's e-commerce sectors per-capita online spending is higher than even the US, according to The Connected Kingdom, a report commissioned by Google and carried out by Boston Consulting Group.\u000a\u000aIt also has the second largest online advertising market in the world after the US, according to consultancy Bain. The internet contributed some 100 billion, or 7.2%, to gross domestic product in 2009.\u000a\u000aPaul Zwillenberg, a partner at BCG said: "Everyone thinks the global Silicon-Valley-based companies are driving growth, but this report makes clear that in the UK it is coming from the 'mom and pop' businesses.\u000a\u000aThey now have global footprints, they are selling to the 'long tail' and they are making their businesses more efficient."
