a((VLast year\u2019s Copenhagen summit on climate change ended on a note of differences between developed and developing nations on several key issues related to climate change and emissions.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aNow, it\u2019s time for yet another World Climate Conference, this time at Cancun, Mexico (November 29 to December 10). Speaking to Deccan Herald, Rajendra Kumar Pachauri, the Chairperson of Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) and the director general of TERI explains, \u201cThe talks should be steered by the science part of it and not by political motives. It\u2019s a political negotiation, but one has to understand the overall concern for every living species which will be affected by the impact of climate change.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAfter the controversial IPCC report on Himalayan glaciers in 2007 and the subsequent retractions, Pachauri lists out what the 2014 report will have.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThere are many new features in the report like cloud cover, black carbon, geo-engineering options, the ethical and equity dimensions of the efforts that are being taken in respect of mitigation of the effects of climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPachauri added that this would include an \u201cupdating of all the other elements of science because new knowledge is emerging and we are going to take that on board. We hope that we can look at regional details to a much greater extent than in the past.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWe have selected 831 authors and review editors out of about 3000 nominations that we received which shows that the scientific community is very enthusiastic about working for the IPCC.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aGeo-engineering\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhat about geo-engineering which finds a mention in the 2014 report? He said, \u201cWe will assess its economic feasibility, its scientific and technical effectiveness and other implications in terms of ecosystems and sustainability. It would be quite pre-mature to form an opinion at this point of time but we are going to assess all the literature that is developing in this field and then come up with clear suggestions.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe IPCC chief who was in Bangalore to attend a programme on sustainable development of infrastructure in Karnataka stressed the importance of looking \u201ctwenty years into the future to devise transport plans which would resolve the present bottlenecks in a city like Bangalore.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThis would require laying down some incentives and some dis-incentives, some regulatory measures to be adopted not only at state level but also at the local level. We would have to ensure that we create capacities, which means training people at various levels.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhen it comes to energy needs and rural areas, Pachauri points out that TERI\u2019s lighting a billion lights programme can take care of the large number of people who live without lights and access to electricity. He added that, \u201cwe are focusing on solar technology and would like to create entrepreneurship at the rural level. It can create clean sustainable lighting in all homes.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHopeful about solar technology\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPachauri is hopeful about the use of solar technology even in cloudy and rainy pockets in rural areas. \u201cThe number of hours of lighting might reduce, but it is still better than not having a light. We have also talked about large scale renewable energy. There are enormous opportunities which are also land intensive in connection with Karnataka.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn places where not a blade of grass grows, there are possibilities of very high insulation of solar energy. It is an opportunity to be explored. In the next four-five years the need for energy in the state will be about 7000 megawatts. For this need there is a requirement of fossil fuel. The other option is to go in for 2000-3000 megawatts of capacity through solar technology. The gestation period is not so long.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHe believes that the right kind of technological innovation and enough manufacturing capacity is needed for implementing the most advanced form of technology for lighting households.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPachauri appreciated the government\u2019s effort to bring in CFL bulbs at a subsidised rates but cautioned about its disposal process keeping in mind the harmful mercury content in these bulbs. He said, it might take four to five years from now to make LED bulbs available in the local markets, but till then CFL can reduce energy consumption to a large extent.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOn curbing emissions\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhat about the role of India in curbing emissions? Pachauri points out that India is a country of well over a billion people and there is a huge disparity of income and growth in this country where resources are finite. He said, \u201cWe are becoming a major exporter of hydrocarbons that has serious implications, so I think India has to work on substitutes for fossil fuels, sooner the better.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt would also be of enormous commercial relevance because now the world is moving in that direction. So I think for a host of domestic and national reasons, India has to pursue a path of sustainable development. In doing so we would certainly be a much lower emitting nation even on per capita basis than other countries of the world.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThat would be our strength not a weakness and an advantage.\u201dHe agreed that traditional ethnic communities have been coping with climate change in the remotest parts of the world. He said, \u201cI think whatever resilience we build in relation to scientific pursuits has to be in addition to whatever we already have as the knowledge base evident within these communities. It is important that we understand this fact and keep focus on the rich traditional knowledge which already exists.\u201d
