a((VAhead of the Cancun climate change conference, about 50 countries on Tuesday began discussions to decide on the best mechanism to ensure that existing technologies that help people in adapting to impacts of climate change are shared with countries that are likely to be the worst affected.\u000a\u000aAn agreement on transfer of technology \u2014 from countries that possess them to ones that need them the most \u2014 is envisaged as one of the several building blocks of a larger international treaty on climate change, for which negotiations are going on for years. These negotiations would take place again at Cancun in Mexico from November 29.\u000a\u000aThe two-day technology seminar, that got underway in New Delhi on Tuesday, is the second in the series. The first was held last year in run-up to the Copenhagen conference.\u000a\u000aOpening the discussions, Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh said the countries, especially from the developing world, needed to focus their energies on evolving a common ground on how technology was to be shared. He said there were existing models for international cooperation that can be replicated for climate change and a knowledge pool created for the benefit of countries that do not have the resources to develop such technologies by themselves.\u000a\u000aRamesh said the Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research, which helped usher in the Green Revolution, was a good example to follow. The countries are expected to leave aside contentious issues \u2014 like how to deal with intellectual property rights \u2014 and concentrate on the broadly agreed principles.\u000a\u000aAfter two days, the countries are expected to come out with a summary of agreements that would be treated as an input for climate change negotiations in Cancun later this month.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
