e could then add $28 to $68 billion more in damages each year from tropical cyclones alone, the report said. The report also said that the number of people exposed to storms and earthquakes in large cities could double to 1.5 billion by 2050.The 250-page report, `Natural Hazards, Unnatural Disasters: The Economics of Effective Prevention' was targeted at the world's finance ministers and stressed on prevention as that alone pays to mitigate the economic impact.It went on to suggest removing rent controls, something India can take notice of as the report pointed out that by doing so, it would bring in incentives for landlords to maintain buildings and thus result in less number of mishaps and deaths. This is important, in view of how a poorly constructed building in Delhi collapsed resulting in 67 deaths.
