a((VThe rich-poor battlelines are drawn more firmly than ever. Expect no surprises in Cancun.\u000a\u000aCopenhagen Flashback\u000a\u000aSummit possibilities\u000a\u000aIndia's Stand\u000a\u000aThe Copenhagen Climate Summit, held from December 6-18, 2009, was roundly dubbed a failure, largely put down to the inflexibility of developed nations. Picking up from Copenhagen will require a relook at the agreements made and not kept in full.The controversial Copenhagen accord asked the rich countries to provide $30 billion of quick money to poorest countries for 2010-2012. It asked the developed countries to provide $100 billion a year by 2020.Developing countries agreed to international consultation and analysis (ICA) of their domestic and voluntary actions to reduce emissions which they would list up with the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change.Trust breaks down between countries with the Copenhagen Accord being forced through and causing bad blood.After Copenhagen, US tried hard to make the Copenhagen Accord the basis of all future negotiations. Developing countries refused to let that happen. Allowed the accord to influence decisions but not become the basic tablet of discussions.US turned on the pressure to make a detailed plan of ICA a pre-condition for talks on other issues.Japan and some others refused to let Kyoto Protocol continue. Some countries make a partial commitment to the $30 billion fast track money but the promises are dodgy.India hosts a climate technology summit, making some progress. Mexico, the host country, tries to push for a 'Mexico Mandate' \u2013 a set of decisions that seem to show a partial deal and a facesaver for the country.The Cancun climate summit will be held from November 29-December 10, 2010, after a series of warm-up meets in Bonn (Germany) and Tianjin (China), where positions have only become more firmly entrenched. Most major issues are likely to end in a stalemate while some other deals could make some progress.The countries have inched closer to getting the basic principles of a technology deal and a forestry deal through, but the details of even these is not in sight yet.The thorny issue of intellectual property rights on climate technologies has been shunted off the table, with US and Europe not keen to discuss it. Risk that it would be taken off for good.No hope of seeing developed countries give their targets under the second phase of Kyoto Protocol that isto start in 2012.Rich countries want as detailed a plan as possible on ICA of developing country actions but developingcountries not keen to let that happen till other elements of the deal \u2013 like targets of rich countries \u2013 are also presented.Developing countries want every element of the deal to be mentioned in the decision(s) that get adopted at Cancun so that progress on fronts amenable to them is also registered.By calling the issues that are close to developing countries' interests tricky and difficult, rich nations would like to push them for later discussions and right now, get other elements discussed.Still going through its split personality phase. It is firmly aligned with the BASIC group and will continue to do so at Cancun. But it's also helping progress on ICA though it does not have backing of China, South Africa and Brazil.PMO has been sitting on proposal to revamp of domestic and international climate governance structure since Shyam Saran resigned. Ex-babus and senior negotiators backed Saran in opposing Jairam Ramesh's line now out in the cold.At home, the committee on low-carbon growth plan set up in wake of the 20-25% emission intensity reduction target is still in limbo. The climate missions are more or less dragging slow, some almost showing little work.
