a((V‘We need to find a common ground with developing countries on climate change mitigation. This could be possible in Cancun’\u000a\u000aAhead of the next round of climate change negotiations at Cancun,Artur Runge-Metzger,Director,International and Climate Strategy for the European Union,spoke to Shalini Nair in Brussels about the trajectory of climate change,the prospects for Cancun and the sticky issues of technology sharing and legally binding emission targets. Excerpts from the interview:\u000a\u000aThis year we have seen an unprecedented heat wave in Russia and devastating floods in Pakistan. Do these have a definite link with global warming and if yes,is there a need to reset our emissions reduction targets?\u000a\u000aAs scientists would tell you,it’s always hard to establish a link between a single weather event and climate change. On the other hand,science also tells us if climate change continues,such events will become frequent. The last Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) assessment report makes it clear that there is an urgency to act and you see that reflected in terms of what happened last year in the Copenhagen climate summit. It was the first time that almost 120 heads of state and government were attending a climate conference—proof that there is awareness at the highest political level to deal with the problem.\u000a\u000aIn comparison to the hoopla that surrounded the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference (UNFCCC) in Copenhagen,the run-up to the next UNFCCC at Cancun this year has been subdued. Is it expected to deliver on some of the gaping questions that Copenhagen left unanswered?\u000a\u000aWhat we saw in Copenhagen was a little wake-up call which showed how far we are still apart on climate change and many things need to be discussed in detail. Then,last year in Copenhagen there was an expectation that the US would pass its climate change legislation. This year we know it is not going to happen. There is willingness from the side of the Obama administration but the political situation in the US is very difficult to get any climate change legislation passed. That is a setback internationally. Many countries will start hiding behind the US and say if a country as rich as US cannot act on climate then why should we when we have not created this problem.\u000a\u000aWhich is not totally unjustified—the average per capita emissions in industrialised countries are ten times more than the average in developing countries. Why then should the BRIC economies (Brazil,Russia,India and China) take on this additional burden of combating climate change when they are not much responsible for it in the first place?\u000a\u000aIf you look at these two groups —the fast-growing developing countries and the developed ones who have established their infrastructure—the former provides maximum opportunities for making savings on emissions. As lot of investment is made in long-term infrastructure—energy,bridges,roads,or transport,it is easier and less expensive to make changes. The rich countries have to support the poorer ones in making the jump to cleaner technologies and in the process both groups are going to save money. That is what we are trying to enshrine in the Clean Development Mechanism (CDM). Of course,richer countries like Europe have an obligation to employ the cleanest technologies and that is the reason we put in place the Emissions Trading System (ETS). Under ETS,when you put a limit on the tonnes of CO2,the power sector is allowed to emit and say the emissions should decline over time,they know it is going to get more expensive over time to emit,making it obligatory for them to move into the low-carbon economy.\u000a\u000aIndia has always quoted its development backlog as the reason not to have legally binding emissions reduction targets. How can India be part of climate action without compromising on its growth story?\u000a\u000aWe believe no country will have to compromise on its growth story while tackling climate change. It’s a different development pattern you will have to follow; it’s a cleaner technology you will have to employ. The immediate extra bill you will have to pay for that is in the end compensated by the bill you will not have to pay for adaption costs. If you look at the carbon footprint of an individual rich person in India and in Europe,the difference is not that big. It’s a matter of the consumption pattern of the rich: is it a fuel efficient car you are driving,it is a matter of how do you heat or cool your house? We need to establish a way of investing in cleaner technologies and some collaboration is required between industrialised and developing countries in making the necessary leap forward. We hope both India and China will compromise with us on the issue of monitoring,reporting and verification of climate change mitigation. We need to find a common ground in order to take this process forward and I think that this could be possible in Cancun soon.
