a((VPrivate Equity\u000a\u000aEarly this week, when renewable energy company Auro Mira Energy raised $21 million from a clutch of private equity investors, founder N Srinivasan pegged the market opportunity for his young company as \u2018enormous\u2019, in light of what he termed the \u201cexploding opportunity in renewable energy\u201d.More entrepreneurs across the country are buying into this point of view, as they set up start-up enterprises in areas such as solar energy development, waste management, LEDs, biofuels and diversified clean energy . Green is in, as the country grapples with multiple issues from crippling power deficiency to high pollution levels.\u201cAt a time when the domestic economy is poised to grow at 8.5% and the government is focusing on financial inclusion, renewable energy offers enormous potential to bridge India\u2019s energy demand-supply gap, which would be required to maintain this projected economic growth,\u201d said Pankaj Sehgal, managing director at SUN Group , a private equity firm. \u201cAlmost half of India\u2019s 1.2 billion people have no access to grid or power supply. Of the 160, 000 mw of power generated in the country, about 18-20% is lost due to inefficient grid and power distribution infrastructure,\u201d he added.Much effort to drive a green agenda in the country is also coming from the government, which is planning to make it mandatory for firms to disclose \u201cgreen initiatives\u201d in their annual reports. Salman Khurshid, minister of corporate affairs, had said earlier this year that companies may be asked to account details on measures taken by them to move towards green technology in their annual reports.This slew of preferential fiscal and regulatory incentives from the government, besides the rising concerns around energy security, is prompting growth in the sector, says Vinod Kala, founder and CEO of Emergent Ventures, a global consulting and finance firm focused on providing services to mitigate climate change.\u201cHigh availability of resources, especially in waste management, and the macro-level investment buzz around the sector are some of the key factors that are driving significant entrepreneurial interest,\u201d he adds. Established in 2004 to support the development of clean development mechanism projects in the carbon market, the firm specialises in areas of wind, biomass gas, biomass combustion, solar and waste management. The company is backed by IDFCApart from the economic and policy factors driving interest in clean technology, opportunity for new business is also coming up, to meet growing consumer demand for more planet-friendly services and products.\u201cPeople are willing to pay a premium for green services now,\u201d says Akshat Rathee, MD at Earth-100 Biofuels, a start-up company that provides corporate customers with a fleet of vehicles that run entirely on biodiesel. Established in 2007, the Gurgaon-based firm today provides an integrated solution including cars modified to run on 100% biodiesel that helps bring down carbon footprint.It also offers add-on services such as convenient dispensing locations, service and maintenance support and performance tracking. The firm is currently supported by Jindal Power as an investor, while Mahindra plays a critical role as technology partner. It has a signed order book of 40 cars, and is negotiating for another 30, said Mr Rathee, who is looking for fresh investments to expand the fleet of cars and to set up back end operations.Total investment in the clean-tech space in the year 2009 stood at $2.7 billion, while the sector attracted investments worth $162 billion globally, as per estimates of New Energy Finance, an information service for the clean technology industry. \u201cWe have identified several companies that we want to fund over the coming months,\u201d said Mr Sehgal of SUN Group, who has been looking at the investment opportunity in the Indian clean-tech sector since 2006.
