a((Vmore-in\u000a\u000aForty per cent of global emissions are attributed to buildings, informs one of the essays in \u2018Social Responsibility and Environmental Sustainability in Business: How organisations handle profits and social duties,\u2019 edited by Preeta M. Banerjee and Vanita Shastri (www.sagepublications.com).\u000a\u000aSustainable building practices can extend building life and provide cost savings, and also enhance employee productivity, as a healthier workplace leads to healthier employees, translating to less absenteeism, greater retention, and improved recruiting, writes the essay\u2019s author, Ameeta Soni. A \u2018green building,\u2019 she explains, \u2018uses less energy, water, and natural resources, creates less waste and is healthier for the people living inside compared to a standard building.\u2019\u000a\u000aDefining sustainability\u000a\u000aSustainability, for starters, is defined as \u2018meeting the needs of today without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs,\u2019 according to the World Commission on Environment and Development. In the context of buildings, what are widely accepted are the standards of LEED (the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design), for both new construction and existing buildings.\u000a\u000aLEED\u2019s rating system has four levels, viz. certified, silver, gold, and platinum, and these are awarded based on the number of credits a building receives for satisfying specific performance benchmarks within various categories of sustainability.\u000a\u000aSix categories in LEED-NC, which governs \u2018new construction,\u2019 are sustainable sites, energy and atmosphere, water efficiency, indoor environmental quality, materials and resources, and innovation in design. LEED-EB, a rating system for \u2018existing buildings\u2019 released in 2004, has one additional category, related to building operation and upgrades.\u000a\u000aExisting buildings\u000a\u000aNew construction techniques still garner the lion\u2019s share of the spotlight when it comes to media coverage related to building sustainability, observes Soni. But it is the facilities that already exist that represent the vast majority of building energy consumption and environmental impact, she adds.\u000a\u000aStatistics mentioned in the essay, relating to the US, speak of existing buildings accounting for 36 per cent of total energy use and 65 per cent of electricity consumption. \u201cThey make up 30 per cent of greenhouse gas emissions and 30 per cent of waste output, a total of 136 million tonnes annually.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhat can be heartening is that in India the rating system is applied with sensitivity to the context, addressing the national priorities. There is higher weight assigned to water efficiency, for example, potable water reduction and using grey water for landscape irrigation, one learns.\u000a\u000aEnergy conservation\u000a\u000aThe author lauds the Energy Conservation Act, 2001, which encourages energy-efficient design or retrofit of commercial buildings that have a connected load of 500 kW or greater, and buildings with conditioned floor area in excess of 1,000 square metres. \u201cIt is currently a voluntary scheme but could be made mandatory within the next few years, potentially yielding an annual savings of 1.7 billion units of power.\u201d\u000a\u000aAptly, she also mentions the Energy Conservation Building Code, ECBC 2007, developed by the Bureau of Energy Efficiency (www.bee-india.nic.in), which is mandatory for commercial buildings and building complexes that have a connected load of more than 500 kW or a contract demand of 600 kVA or greater.\u000a\u000aThree stages\u000a\u000aGriha, you may know as \u2018house\u2019 in Sanskrit. But what is GRIHA? An acronym for Green Rating for Integrated Habitat Assessment, a tool developed by TERI (The Energy and Resources Institute - www.teriin.org) for measuring and rating a building\u2019s environmental performance in the context of India\u2019s varied climate and building practices. This tool, adopted by the Ministry of New and Renewable Energy, uses qualitative and quantitative assessment criteria to rate a building on the degree of its greenness. The rating has the potential be applied to new and existing building stock of varied functions, the essay notes.\u000a\u000aThe \u2018basic features\u2019 of GRIHA, as described in www.grihaindia.org, speak of a system to help \u2018design and evaluate\u2019 new buildings, by assessing predicted performance over entire lifecycle \u2013 inception through operation. The first of the three stages of the lifecycle is \u2018pre-construction stage\u2019 with a focus on issues such as proximity to public transport, type of soil, kind of land, where the property is located, the flora and fauna on the land before construction activity starts, the natural landscape and land features.\u000a\u000aThe second stage is of \u2018building planning and construction,\u2019 where the issues are of resource conservation and reduction in resource demand, resource utilisation efficiency, resource recovery and reuse, and provisions for occupant health and wellbeing. And the third stage is of \u2018building operation and maintenance,\u2019 where attention is paid, among other things, to monitoring and recording of energy consumption.\u000a\u000aSavings in store\u000a\u000aTERI\u2019s work finds cited, again, in a section on reaping the benefits of green. Audits by TERI have revealed that annual energy bill can be saved 5 to 25 per cent, and therefore payback for recommended changed can be less than three years. A large portion of these savings are from the air-conditioning systems, and the remainder from areas such as lighting, Soni writes.\u000a\u000aSome countries have woken up to the need to incentivise energy efficiency, through concessional utility rates for energy-saving HVAC (heating, ventilating, and air-conditioning) equipment, and newer models of computer that employ more power-efficient processors.\u000a\u000aFor instance, \u201cin the US, Energy Star programs currently enable owners or designers of new or existing commercial buildings to taka a tax deduction of up to $1.80 per square foot if they save at least 50 per cent of the heating and cooling energy of a building that meets American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) standards for energy-efficient design.\u201d\u000a\u000aHopes on the horizon\u000a\u000aA recent paper in http://new.evomarkets.com, titled \u2018Energy Efficiency in the US and India: A study in contrasts and possibilities\u2019 sees hope in venture capital funding to support companies that manufacture energy-efficient products and provide related services in the sector, in India. \u201cStay tuned; Indian policy is rapidly evolving with numerous favourable programmes on the horizon,\u201d conclude the paper\u2019s authors Patrick McCloskey and Stanley Trybulski of Evolution Markets Financial Services.\u000a\u000aRecommended \u2018green\u2019 read.
