a((Vmore-in\u000a\u000aClimate change has caused two species to emerge from one, according to a genetic study on white-bellied shortwing, a small bird species found only in the Western Ghats.\u000a\u000aThe study conducted by V.V. Robin, Anindya Sinha and Uma Ramakrishnan of the National Institute of Advanced Studies, Bangalore, and National Centre for Biological Sciences, Bangalore, reveals that the Western Ghats, the Palghat Gap and the Shencottah Gap, both of which provide major rail and road connectivity across the Western Ghats between Kerala and Tamil Nadu, caused a break in the populations of the species.\u000a\u000aMillion years' story\u000a\u000aThe populations across the Palghat Gap got separated 5 million years ago, and the Nilgiris and Anamalai hills, to the north and south of the gap, harbour two different species of the white-bellied shortwing. Across the Shencottah Gap, the populations were separated about 2 million years ago.\u000a\u000aThe researchers argue that the single species of white-bellied shortwing should be split into two different species \u2014 white-bellied shortwing and rufous-bellied shortwing on either side of the Palghat Gap. These were the names used earlier by ornithologist Salim Ali.\u000a\u000aThey are of the view that glacial cycles, especially the ice ages, may also have played an important role in splitting these species.\u000a\u000aIce Age impact\u000a\u000aDuring the Ice Age, the tropical regions got drier, driving species adapted to wet-forest conditions higher up into the mountains where they then became isolated. The most recent ice age about 20,000 years ago had also impacted these species.\u000a\u000aThese isolated populations on mountaintops were severely affected as the forests shrunk drastically and they went through a massive population decline.\u000a\u000aWhen the Ice Age ended and the forests recovered, the survivors of the species multiplied to the current population, according to the researchers.\u000a\u000aHigh elevation species are strongly affected by climatic change.\u000a\u000aAs it gets warmer, these species move higher up on mountains and face greater threat of extinction due to global warming. But the climate has been changing since millennia.\u000a\u000aHowever, the DNA of the species retains signatures of past population changes. Genetic tools can then be used to understand species response to past climate change, they said.\u000a\u000aThe study reveals how species respond to changes in climate based on their ecology. Such information will help predict how species may respond to future climate change allowing more targeted conservation.\u000a\u000aThe focus is on how the species got to these island mountain tops of the Ghats and the extent of relatedness among populations on different islands, they said.
