a((VTill a few years ago, climate change was the elephant in the room at global development forums. Leaders were aware of it but either chose not to see it or denied it had consequences that could be even remotely catastrophic. Things have changed since, quite dramatically. Today, climate change is viewed as a problem of elephantine proportions.Things have moved up a notch from last year, which ended with the much publicized no-show at the Copenhagen summit . Not only has a global consensus emerged that climate change is for real, but there\u2019s increasing discussion about the tricky question of action required to contain it.While much scientific literature, as well as striking images, is available on the devastation that greenhouse gases have been wreaking on the globe \u2013 glacial and polar ice melts, rising global mean temperatures and sea levels \u2013 what is now needed is more country-specific research and discussion on the hazards ahead and ways to mitigate them."Climate Change, Society & Sustainable Development: Agenda for Action", makes a good beginning in this direction, for India. It\u2019s a collection of papers by experts \u2013 scientific researchers, agriculture agriculture and energy specialists, policy-planners, non-governmental voices and advocacy groups. It presents both the wide arc of the problem as well as a deeper look into the sectoral issues involved.The book aims to, according to the foreword by M S Swaminathan , father of the Green Revolution , provide information that would help "develop a strategy for sustainable human security in our country". That may sound ambitious but the book\u2019s multi-disciplinary approach is the right way to go about understanding these issues in India.However, it has some limitations. These are imposed by our current level of knowledge. For instance, veteran glaciologist Syed Iqbal Hasnain in his paper on the Hindu Kush and Himalayan glaciers points to the need for more on-site research to better understand the dynamics of melting and downwasting of glaciers. Climate scientist S K Dash, while touching on differential temperature increases in regions, prolonged fog in cities and changes in rainfall patterns, also calls for more data. That said, the book will serve both the serious reader who wants to look at the intertwined shoots and branches of the climate problem, and the policy planner for whom it would be a ready reckoner of sorts.
