a((VBANGALORE: How do changes in climate affect species and biodiversity ? A study by scholars from Bangalore-based National Institute of Advanced Studies ( NIAS ) and National Centre for Biological Sciences ( NCBS ) has shown that climate change infact caused the emergence of two species from one in the case of some small birds in the mountains of western ghats A genetic study conducted by V V Robin, Anindya Sinha and Uma Ramakrishnan from NIAS and NCBS examined how a species of bird found only in the western ghats, the white-bellied shortwing, gave rise to two species of birds.According to an NCBS release, their genetic data found that the major geographical gaps in the western ghats, the Palghat gap and the Shencottah gap, both of which today provide major rail and road connectivity across the western ghats (between Kerala and Tamil Nadu), caused a break in the population of the species.Population across Palghat gap separated five million years ago, and the Nilgiris and Anamalai hills, to the north and south of this gap, harbour two different species of the white-bellied shortwing. Across the smaller Shencottah Gap, population separated about two million years ago. The study of these species by the three scholar shows that single species of thebird can now be split into two different species -- white-bellied shortwing and rufous-bellied shortwing -- on either side of the Palakkad Gap. These were names used by legendary Indian ornithologist, Salim Ali.Interestingly, glacial cycles, especially the ice ages, may also have played an important role in splitting these species, scientists say. During the ice ages, the tropical regions got drier, driving species adapted to wet-forest conditions higher up into the mountains where they became isolated.According to the study, the most recent ice age about 20,000 years ago also impacted these species. These isolated populations on mountaintops were severely affected, and as forests shrunk drastically, they went through a massive population decline. When the ice age ended and forests recovered, the survivors multiplied to give us the current population, the NCBS study says.It provides an example of how species respond to changes in climate based on their ecology. Such information will help predict how species may respond to future climate change allowing more targeted conservation.The Western Ghats is a biodiversity hotspot, and forests on hill tops here (called sky-islands) harbour highly specialised species not found in lowland forests. These specialised plants and animals are virtually trapped on these islands, and studying them gives clues to their origin.High elevation species are strongly affected by climatic change and as it gets warmer, species move higher up on mountains. These species therefore face greater threat of extinction due to global warming. So genetic tools can then be used to understand their response to past climate change.
