a((VAHMEDABAD: The 11-day Common Wealth Games (CWG) 2010, which concluded recently in New Delhi, produced 1.28 lakh tonnes of carbon emissions.The estimate was done by a team of students of the post graduate programme in management (PGP) at the Indian Institute of Management - Ahmedabad ( IIM-A ) as part of its academic project.The second-year students - -Bhanu Prabha, A Pratheeba and Tabassum Perween - had used secondary data from various sources to separately calculate the carbon footprints of the event, including transportation, construction, electricity, food and beverages, the opening and closing ceremonies and even the CWG Queens Baton.The project, under the guidance of professor at IIM-A Amit Garg, revealed that out of nine major stadiums whose carbon footprints were analysed, SP Mukherjee stadium released 1,100 tonnes of carbon dioxide (CO2), which is the largest.Tabassum said, \u201cA technology called \u2018screw chiller\u2019 used to maintain the water temperature of swimming pools has contributed to the stadium\u2019s high carbon emissions. With an emission of 14 tonnes of CO2, the least polluting stadium turned out to be Dr Karni Singh stadium, where shooting competitions were held.The students said that the proper arrangement of seating to accommodate the maximum number of audience, the process of conducting the events, and its design, apart from its size, play a significant role in deciding the carbon emission of a stadium.The students said that the actual carbon footprint of CWG, if different from their estimation, can only be higher than the figures they have arrived at. Prabha said, \u201cSince we were not present at the event and had no access to precise data, we have adopted a very conservative estimation. So, in a way, the figure we have projected is the minimum if not the exact.\u201d According to the students\u2019 report, out of the 1.28 lakh tonnes of C02 emitted at various CWG venues, 70 per cent comes from the use of electricity during different phases of the event, including the construction of infrastructure, lighting of the stadiums, power consumption at the Games Village and so on.The second major cause of pollution was transportation, which accounted for 21 per cent of the total figure. The maximum carbon footprint came from organizers and players who flew down to Delhi.The students suggested that pollution from transportation could be cut down by optimizing air transportation of the payers through prior planning and co-ordination to avoid vacant seats on flights.The students also suggested that the carbon footprint of each player be calculated and companies should be asked to sponsor it. The organizers, players and the audience must reduce their own carbon footprints, they suggested. An attempt to offset the carbon footprint is the next step, said Garg.
