a((VPUNE: Solar energy-powered hand pumps have been launched by a city-based company to help villagers draw water from wells without manually operating them.The pumps, developed by Span Pumps Private Limited , help save time and energy required to pump ground water. They can make a difference in rural areas that suffer from power shortage or those which have not been electrified.The company has drawn up a rate contract with the Maharashtra Energy Development Authority (MEDA), the nodal agency of the state government for renewable energy initiatives. The system will be subsidised by the Union government.The first such solar water pump was installed by the gram panchayat of Talegaon Dhamdhere in Pune district earlier this week. Zilla Parishad president Savita Dagde was present.Nitiyan Mutiyan, director of Span Pumps, said, "A large percentage of India's rural communities depend on borewells for drinking water. These borewells are fit with hand pumps. It takes about 40 strokes to fill a bucket of water. The solar-operated submersible pumps will help draw between 5,000 to 20,000 litres every day. It will operate automatically on solar power and store water in an overhead tank."The pumping system consists of the pump and solar array. It has been specially developed for borewells, said development consultant Narendra Purankar. "A solar array (300-800 W) is installed near the borewell. A pump is installed below the hand pump cylinder, and works on power generated from photovoltaic solar cells. Both the submersible and hand pumps share the same pipes. Unlike other solar systems, the new system operates without battery or an inverter. The pump draws power from the solar array directly. The pump is connected to a storage tank and water is dispensed through a stand post," he said.On a regular day, the pump operates for about 7-8 hours between sunrise and sunset. After sunset or when solar power is not available the users can pump to draw water. The system has a back-up and ensures uninterrupted water supply."The initial installation cost is between Rs 2.5 and Rs 4.5 lakh depending on the capacity of the solar array and the pump. "Solar power is free and there is no loss or wastage of power. Besides, the solar panel will last for 15-20 years, and both operations and maintenance costs are low," Purankar said.So far, 50 such pumps have been installed in Gujarat, Rajasthan and Uttar Pradesh, and 15 pumps have been exported to African countries, Mutiyan said.Eom//kscleared/mdStory-Istory: Solar powered hand pumps for rural areasTimes News NetworkPune: Solar energy powered hand pumps have been launched by a city based company to help villagers draw water from wells without the laborious manual pumping process.The pumps developed by Span Pumps Private Limited help save time and energy in pumping ground water, mainly in rural areas which are not reached by electricity. The company has a rate contract with the Maharashtra Energy Development Authority (MEDA) - the nodal agency of the state government for renewable energy initiatives and the system will be subsidised by the Union government.The first solar water pump in the state was installed by the gram panchayat of Talegaon Dhamdhere in Pune district earlier this week in the presence of Savita Dagde, president, Zilla Parishad.Addressing a news conference on Friday, Nitiyan Mutiyan , director, Span Pumps said: "A large percentage of India's rural communities depend on borewells for drinking water supplies. These borewells are fitted with handpumps, which are the backbone of the rural water supply programme; however, it takes about 40 pump strokes to fill just a bucket of water--a process that is both time-consuming and laborious. The solar operated submerisible pumps will help pump anywhere between 5,000 to 20,000 litres of water a day. It will operate automatically on solar power and store water in an overhead tank."The solar powered borewell pumping system---which will consist of the pump and s