a((VThe Monsoon session witnessed the clearing of the Energy Conservation (amendment) Bill, 2010. The Bill has pushed the nation to a regime of energy tradea way perceived by many, including me, as a back-door entry to the carbon (emission) trade regime, which the nation, irrespective of the party at the helm, has opposed in all international forums, tooth and nail, till date. Characteristic of the Congress-led UPA government, the market has been given its way out, irrespective of the priority of the masses.\u000a\u000aThe Bill ostensibly proposes that the Energy Conservation Building Code will be made mandatory for all buildings with a certain level of electricity load, an approach that has a complete emphasis on demand side management. On the other hand, the manufacturers, importers and suppliers of equipment, appliances and services will be free to continue with their business-as-usual approach and perpetuate inefficient technologies for a considerable period of time. The new legislation allows one entity to trade in its surplus energy points with some other entity, which is not energy efficient. Carbon credit mechanisms on emissions are in vogue in the world and a similar action seems to have been suggested at the domestic level.\u000a\u000aThe passage of the Bill effectively means that the Indian consumers, who are already struggling because our country has become a sellers market, will be further penalised in the form of bearing the high initial cost of energy-efficiency equipment, appliances and services. If the government is really concerned about the welfare of the consumers, it should have proposed an amendment Bill that is based on the dictum of supply-side management in which manufacturers, importers etc, are barred from producing appliances, equipment and services below a pre-defined level of energy efficiency.\u000a\u000aThere are many successful models of such supply-side management elsewhere in the world. For example, there is this Top Runners Programme in Japan in which the basis for the adoption of standards is pre-defined as the use-phase energy performance of the best technology available on the market. Exact standard levels, however, along with appropriate target years, are agreed on via an extensive consultative processes involving several stakeholder groups. Thereafter, when promulgated by the regulator, the targets become mandatory for all manufacturers and importers. In this manner, the industry will not only receive self-stimulus for continuous improvement but this will also help produce indigenous world leaders in technology.\u000a\u000aTo the contrary, the new Indian legislation is now all set to produce mediocres simply for the reason that the proposed Perform Achieve and Trade (PAT) mechanism under the National Mission on Enhanced Energy Efficiency proposes to set standards based on the industrys average rather than the industrys best. In fact, there will be no real energy saving in the country because for the PAT mechanism to be successful, some industries will be performing better than the average to earn Energy Saving Certificates while others have to perform below the average to buy those certificates. Indias quest for becoming a global leader in manufacturing and industry would remain a dream for ever.\u000a\u000aThe legislation is not only anti-consumer but also anti-poor. There is nothing in the new legislation that can assure us that the energy saved by richer consumers and big industries would be preferentially used by small entrepreneurs and villagers for whom the marginal productivity of any additional electricity use is much higher compared to big industries and large consumers. These small entrepreneurs and poor villagers will continue to struggle for a flicker of light for even 2-3 hours a day.\u000a\u000aWhile the common man in the rural hinterland is happy riding alongside 100 people in a bus packed to its capacity, it is the wrong priority of the government that allows precious taxpayer money to be wasted in subsidising fuel for luxury cars carrying individuals in the metros. Add on the costs of roads, bridges, flyovers, expressways, all catering to the needs of a few individuals, while the overwhelming energy efficient majority in villages still await its turn.\u000a\u000aPerhaps the whole scheme of things fits well with the development design of the Planning Commission, which is finding peace in blaming the poor record of energy efficiency on farmers and even in arguing that subsidised electricity to these extravagant farmers must be stopped to enhance ground water level.\u000a\u000aBodies like the Planning Commission can afford to conveniently forget that poor farmers are only reducing their risk and securitising themselves against erratic power and canal water supply by putting up redundantly large irrigation pumps. The fair question is that, where does the subsidy of Rs 7,000 crore provided in the Budget (for the year 2010-11) of the ministry of power go Not to the aam aadmi!\u000a\u000aThe author, a Rajya Sabha MP, is a national spokesman for the BJP
