a((VEfficiency and sustainability have become the twin mantras that gained currency in the aftermath of the economic slowdown. In this process, smart infrastructure is expected to play an important role. In India, infrastructure is an area of high-priority area for the government. And within infrastructure, Mission 2012: Power to Alla comprehensive blueprint that encompasses generation, transmission, distribution and conservationis an attempt by the government to ensure sufficient, reliable and quality power at optimum cost.\u000a\u000aInterestingly, what seems like an ambitious goal is well within reach through one of the most exciting and potent concepts of all timessmart grid. This state-of-the-art technology integrates an entire power grid system into a single, interactive real-time network to ensure improved performance and reliability while eliminating waste to reduce the environmental impact. In fact, smart grids optimise not just generation and distribution but also consumption. And with their ability to consolidate power from conventional and clean energy sources, they reduce CO2 emissions to the extent it's technically feasible.\u000a\u000aThe traditional power grid is based on centralised generation plants that supply consumers via long-established, unidirectional transmission & distribution (T&D) systems. In contrast, the smart grid is an advanced version, an intelligent system that not only delivers reliable supplies on demand but also receives power of all qualities from all sourcesboth centralised and distributed.\u000a\u000aFor instance, visualise a home where residents keep track of their energy spending. A smart meter helps run the washing machine during offpeak hours and the dishwasher, too, in order to make use of lower tariffs. Whats more, the house has solar panels and a mini-wind turbine installed on the roof. Therefore, instead of using energy from the grid, the residents can bank upon their own energy production, and even sell the extra energy to the grid. Though this concept sounds futuristic, experiments across the world show that it is possible and has become popular in the US, Germany, Spain and Italy, among other nations.\u000a\u000aWhat makes the smart grid special is the fact that it is environment-friendly. For instance, according to a research sponsored by the US government, improving the efficiency of the national electricity grid by 5% would be equivalent of eliminating the carbon emissions and fuel use of 53 million cars. This digital system of electricity distribution not only negates waste but also opens up the market for alternative energy producers of all sizes, by decentralising energy production.\u000a\u000aUndoubtedly, this is an exciting concept, and the world is latching on to it. US President Barack Obama last year passed an $11-billion stimulus package for smart grid technology and for expanding transmission to renewable rich areas. The 30% increase in funding was to kickstart the project that would also include smart meters. In Germany, the Meregio (minimum emission region) project has taken off for pilot deployment.\u000a\u000aIn fact, the whole world is waking up to the fact that it will be impossible to meet the increasing energy demands without investing in smart grids. According to a KPMG study, even in the current low-growth scenario, India would need to increase its installed capacity to at least 183 gw by 2012 from the existing 132 gw. The challenge is that Indias T&D losses are one of the highest in the world, averaging at 50% after taking power theft into account. Installing smart grid is the best way the country can rein in the losses and ramp up generation to meet the energy needs of its growing economy.\u000a\u000aThe Indian government has initiated the accelerated power development & reform programme (APDRP) in 2001. The programme aims to strengthen sub-T&D networks, thus reducing the aggregate technical & commercial (AT&C) losses. In 2008, the restructured APDRP or R-APDRP released the revised terms and conditions, with the focus on actual and demonstrable performance in terms of sustained loss reduction.\u000a\u000aTill date, 27 states have either notified or constituted their regulatory commissions with 100% feeder metering achieved in 20 states. In a first of its kind project in the world, the Karnataka Power Transmission Corporation Ltd (KPTCL) has attempted to strengthen its power networks and the constituent distribution utilities.\u000a\u000aWith a consumer base of almost 16 million and plans to add about 10,000 mw power in the next few years, KPTCLs T&D is multiplying every year. The integrated Scada solution will include monitoring 867 T&D stations with one million input/output points across Karnataka from a single control room in real time in Bangalore.\u000a\u000aThe project will help KPTCL manage distributed generation from independent power producers), non-conventional energy producers and mini hydel plants in the KPTCL grid. A significant step in the direction of making the grid smart, this project will also help reduce line losses, voltage irregularities and energy billing.\u000a\u000aThe world over, the clamour today is for renewable energy sources that are also cost-efficient. A smart grid is the right way forward for India as well. Being a new concept, research and implementation is taking place at almost the same breath. In this context, countries like India and China, which need to increase their power supply exponentially each year, can set examples using smart grid, especially for newer networks.\u000a\u000aHowsoever we try, there are no short cuts to reach the dual targets of meeting energy needs while staying green. Plugging the leakages and maximising efficiencies will be the answer for a long time. In all probability, turning smart has never been more advantageous than now.\u000a\u000aThe author is the head of power systems division at ABB India
