a((VHanshlal Tusliram Hande and Bhimabai Hande had a simple formula to turn around their village, Wankute in Sangamner taluka of Maharashtra's Ahmednagar district. The Handes along with other members of the Jai Malhar Village Watershed Committee began with the slogan of voluntary labour for village development. Soon, the strength swelled to an army of villagers.Wankute has now emerged as an oasis of hope that can fend off the worst of droughts. The Jai Malhar Village Watershed Committee was one of the recipients for the JSW-The Times of India Earth Care Awards 2010. Bhimabhai Hande said, "Our watershed is now managed by the community. We ensure not a drop goes waste."Recognising efforts like these by communities, corporate entities and NGOs, a gala function was organised in the capital on Friday to award winners of the second JSW-The Times of India Earth Care Awards. MoS for IT and communications Sachin Pilot was the chief guest.In his inaugural speech, Vineet Jain, Times Group Managing Director, pointed out that "a decade ago only a small group of scientists and a smaller group of policymakers were aware of the threats from climate change". He said in the ensuing 10 years, the concerns of environment and climate change had got mainstreamed with the issues, "forcing them into public perception". He also waded into the development versus environment debate: "A rapidly-growing economy such as ours faces a big dilemma: Development versus environment. Capping carbon emission could slow down growth. And growth is the only way out of poverty. The challenge is to look beyond mutually exclusive, zero-sum scenarios. Can we find win-win paths to growth? I believe we need to hasten the development of clean technologies, and embrace eco-friendly alternatives. We need attractive incentives in the form of tax breaks, lower tariffs and R&D grants to persuade industry to go green. And we need to punish those who violate energy-efficiency solutions.""Even as world leaders try to work towards a climate treaty, we at the Times... have chosen to use the most potent weapon at our disposal \u2014 to create public awareness about climate change, and to share knowledge of best practices both within and outside the country.To those who think the human race can carry on with its old and unsustainable ways of living and doing business, I can only say, time is not a luxury we have. This is one decision we cannot postpone," he added.Sangeeta Jindal, head of Jindal Foundation, talked of the challenges posed by climate change along with the hope raised by this year's awardees. She said the task of the jury, that included IPCC chief R K Pachauri, agriculture scientist M S Swaminathan and Kartikeya Sarabhai of Centre for Environment Education, was much harder since there were more than 50 applicants in the fray.Pachauri recollected policy-making in the 1980s when environment was still a fringe issue, and stressed that the corporate sector must spearhead the search for solutions to climate change.A panel of four eminent experts \u2014 Chandra Bhushan, deputy director of Centre for Science and Environment, S Parasuraman, director of Tata Institute of Social Sciences, Shailaja Chandra,former chief secretary of Delhi, and C L L Gowda of ICRISAT \u2014 highlighted the climate change challenges and the way forward.
