a((VAs the curtains come down on the three-day Summer Davos conference in Tianjin today, you can't help but take away two strong impressions. One, the daunting challenges facing the world in the early years of the 21st century, particularly those surrounding sustainability which can be addressed only through unprecedented collaboration on the part of business, governments, and society. Two, as we try to meet these challenges, China will play a central but still uncertain role.From the cascade of information that unfolded at Tianjin, all thoughts continued to gravitate towards the events central theme \u2014 Driving Growth Through Sustainability mentored by renowned global business leaders like Eckhard Cordes , chairman of the management board and CEO of Metro Group , the German retailer; Klaus Kleinfeld, chairman and CEO of Alcoa, John S Watson, chairman of the board and CEO, Chevron Corporation . In fact James E Rogers, chairman, president and CEO of Duke Energy Corporation even went on record to state that, within our company, every action, every decision, is made through the lens of sustainability.The issue may be fairly complex but we can get a lot done if businesses are more inclusive and responsible, governments more accountable and society and individuals more alert and participative in their future. What was clear across these multiple debates on sustainability was that no one group can tackle an issue as broad and complex as generating environmentally sustainable economic growth.There has to be a multi-step framework that we need to employ towards this end. First, we have to establish the need for sustainability so that everyone sees it as a win from their point of view i.e. increased profits like quality, increase votes for governments because of awareness amongst citizens and better health. Secondly, we need to figure out how to measure progress through a combination of initiatives like establishment of measurement standards, making disclosures of carbon footprint mandatory and regulation to ensure compliance in defaulting industries and social practices, and finally incentivize action to achieve it. Tom Enders, CEO of Airbus made an interesting point in this context. He said that "we need central funding to drive cross-industry research in alternate fuels, biosciences and nanotechnology to avoid parallel research and restricted access as accelerated implementation of solution is in everyone's interest."Governments and consumers are also integral parts of the solution, and their immediate interests may conflict with those of business and with each other. So which of these parties should will take the lead in creating the difficult but necessary collaboration required to make measurable progress? What are the incentives to get one of the parties to take such a step? Who will finance this change in relationships?The meeting in Tianjin didn't provide answers but you can't find answers until you've identified the right questions.There is hope though as two social innovators reminded us. Gemma Bulos and her Single Drop of safe water initiative in Philippines and Sakena Yacoobi who leads the Afghan institute of learning for education and health for Afghan women and children and won the Social Entrepreneur of the year award \u2014 both making a big difference in a large pool of problems. These individual remind you that there is indeed hope if you take the first step forward.However, one question that continued to nag me is related to China's role in solving a thorny global issue like sustainability. Cheng Siwei, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congresss statement sums it up well, By the year's end, factories that do not meet energy efficiency requirements will be shut down and their bosses will be punished. If one needed to be reminded that one was in China, this statement pretty much did! You always take a politicians words with a grain of salt, of course. But that feeling was heightened by my ambiguous feelings about China itself.
