a((VTwenty years, 25 amendments, several committees and notifications after, the issue of regulating development along India's coastlines remains under debate. The latest to run into a roadblock is the draft notification of the Coastal Regulation Zone 2010, allowing slum redevelopment within the no-go zone (with private participation) and tourism facilities along shorelines - seen as a potential unleashing of construction and consequent ecological destruction.The first rules to regulate the country's 7,500km coastline came through in 1991. They were followed by a phenomenal 25 amendments in the next two decades. Then, in an attempt to provide a systematic overhaul to the coastal regime, a committee was formed under M S Swaminathan in 2004. The committee ran into controversy. Oddly, the fisherfolk communities as well as the builder lobbies opposed the report tooth and nail.The Union environment and forests ministry came up with a draft Coastal Management Zone regulations in 2008 which most claimed had selectively used by the government to push for changes it already was intending to bring in. But a tide of protests ensured that the draft never got accepted by the MoEF.In 2009, yet another committee was set up, with M S Swaminathan and Centre for Science and Environment director Sunita Narain as two experts from outside the government, along with M S Mauskar, additional secretary with the environment and forests ministry.The report politely asked for the earlier committee recommendations to be junked and a reinforcement of the original 1991 rules, with stricter monitoring and regulation. It also recommended a stronger regime to protect the fisherfolk and their rights.Based on the new report, Union environment and forests minister Jairam Ramesh undertook public hearings across the country - an intelligent move to get political and social buy in \u2013 and the ministry came up with a 'pre-draft' Coastal Management Zone regulations which were put up for public comment.But the controversy over the six-year process didn't end there. Every interested party, from fisherfolk groups and environmental NGOs to state governments reacted strongly to the pre-draft version. More than 150 substantial comments poured in.One of the authors of the second report, Sunita Narain, reacted sharply to the pre-draft version, claiming that the proposed rules did not go by the recommendations she and her colleagues had made. She said that the rules by sleight of hand were imposing the regime that the earlier M S Swaminathan report had suggested and most had protested against. She also slammed the exceptions the proposed rules make for states like Kerala and Goa and cities like Mumbai.The MoEF, after receiving comments on the 'pre-draft' version has now come up with a draft notification. Some of the key areas of dispute remain embedded in the draft notification and the government will now have to resolve these before it can end the 6-year impasse on how to regulate development along the vast coastline of the country.Among the key issues being debated is that the new draft could be used to do away with the 500m high tide line no-development zone that is imposed at present.The 25 amendments brought in over the last two decades, some of them extremely contentious, have been accepted into the new draft. These include amendments that allow the Navi Mumbai airport, nuclear power plants, special economic zones and tourism facilities to come up along the shoreline.Besides, the government has also agreed to a special dispensation for Mumbai to redevelop slums, which could lead to an unmanageable housing boom along the already crowded shoreline and displace the poor. Similar dispensations forKerala and Goa too could provide space for backdoor entry to large land developers.While a key demand, through the two decades, was to protect the livelihood and rights of traditional fisherfolk living and working along the coast, the ministry of environment and forests has deferred the move by shifting the onus on the agriculture ministry to come up with a new set of rules or a law to do so.
