a((VThe US-India military-to-military relationship is dynamic, strategic and multifaceted, and one of the most important parts of the overall US-India partnership. Our defence relations have evolved from primarily military-to-military exchanges to a more comprehensive relationship that encompasses dialogues, exchanges, exercises, defence sales and practical cooperation.\u000a\u000aAction, or in this case, travel and attention, speak louder than words. As proof that the US-India military relationship is growing and expanding, US Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Admiral Mike Mullen, commander of the US Pacific Command Admiral Robert Willard, Deputy Secretary of Defence William Lynn, and Undersecretary for Defense for Policy Michele Flournoy all have visited India in 2010. This week, US Secretary of Defence Gates will host Minister of Defence AK Antony in Washington to discuss regional and global security and further advance our military relationship.\u000a\u000aOne of the key features of the US National Security Strategy, released in May, is the focus of American engagement on galvanising the collective action that can serve common interests such as combating violent extremism, stopping the spread of nuclear weapons and securing nuclear materials, and forging cooperative solutions to the threat of climate change, armed conflicts and pandemic diseases. The starting point of that collective action will be our engagement with partners so that we can cooperate on issues of regional and global concern, with the recognition that power, in an interconnected world, is no longer a zero-sum game.\u000a\u000aIt is no accident, therefore, that the US National Security Strategy calls the relationship with India a top priority, as the US and Indias specific security interests are converging. The US and Indian perspectives are increasingly viewed through a strategic prismseeing common interests, shared outcomes and identical threats.\u000a\u000aFor example, both countries have a mutual interest in the free passage in the Indian Ocean and surrounding waterways. The US and Indian economies and our continued prosperity will rely on effective maritime security that can be provided by increased cooperation between our two navies and coast guards, which is just one of the many areas of expanded cooperation mentioned in the Counterterrorism Cooperation Initiative that our governments signed in July.\u000a\u000aBoth countries have a mutual interest in countering the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. Working together, our efforts can help counter this threat to regional and global security. Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and President Barack Obama worked on this issue together at a summit in April 2010.\u000a\u000aBoth countries have a mutual interest in the long-term stability and reconstruction of Afghanistan. The US is committed to deepening and building a strategic partnership that addresses security, prosperity and development for an independent Afghanistan. India is doing its part, playing a positive role in Afghanistans economic and social development, which the US strongly supports. Indias continued involvement will play a key part in Afghanistans future success. We both view this challenge in the same strategic manner.\u000a\u000aWith so many shared security interests, it is not surprising that our military relationship has expanded and deepened in the past five years.\u000a\u000aIndia is now conducting more exercises with American forces than it is with any other nation in the world. We now have regular exercises across all services that are growing in complexity as both militaries become more familiar with each other. As an example, India has sent a team of naval and army officers to participate in the Habu Nag exercises in Okinawa.\u000a\u000aAs our interests and vision for the future converge, so do the technology and weapons systems. The first of six C-130J military transport aircraft will be delivered in December, on time and on budget. We hope to finalise the sale of C-17 transport aircraft in the next few months and two US companies have made strong bids for the medium multi-role combat aircraft tender. Selecting either of these companies would be a very strong signal of Indias commitment to our global military partnership.\u000a\u000aA vitally important aspect to this building relationship entails helping people and responding to natural disasters. Earthquakes, tsunamis and floods will occur in this region, maybe with more frequency. Whether the scenario involves humanitarian assistance, counterterrorism cooperation, or maritime security activities, having common equipment will allow more seamless cooperation.\u000a\u000aRecognising the importance of seamless cooperation, the Obama Administration has made export control reform a key priority as we see streamlining and modernising our export control system as a national security issue. This directly affects our ability to build effective partnerships with partners such as India.\u000a\u000aAlong similar lines, we encourage India to sign the agreements that are vital to develop the full potential for the US to transfer the most sophisticated technology in the world. This enables joint research and development, technology collaboration and increased US investment, and is necessary for India to benefit fully from our most sensitive military equipment and highly sophisticated encryption technology.\u000a\u000aHistory has shown that global problems and challenges can only be overcome by collective action. World War II was won by countries from North and South America, Europe, and Asia working together. The Cold War was won through the collective efforts of the US, Western Europe and many other countries. Current and future global problems and challenges can only be solved in a similar manner. Partnering with India, the global commons can be safer. By expanding our already robust cooperation in air, space, cyberspace and maritime initiatives, the region can be a more prosperous and peaceful place.\u000a\u000aAs President Obama told the recent graduating class at West Point, The burdens of this century cannot fall on American shoulders alone. In the past, weve always had the foresight to avoid acting alone. A secure and peaceful world requires partners with common security interests that are willing and able to partner with us. We are building that partnership.\u000a\u000aThe author is the US Ambassador to India
